<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 1917EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-AIDS     11-02 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-AIDS,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Would Fight AIDS Discrimination, Aide Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush would use the power of the
presidency to push for federal legislation banning discrimination
against people with the AIDS virus, the Bush campaign's top domestic
affairs adviser said Wednesday.
   Deborah Steelman's assertion was an extension of Bush's own
support for the White House AIDS commission's recommendation last
summer calling for a federal antidiscrimination law as the
foundation for a more aggressive fight against the disease.
   Meeting with a small group of reporters, Steelman was reminded
that conservative Republicans _ particularly Sen. Jesse Helms of
North Carolina and Rep. William E. Dannemeyer _ were successful in
blocking antidiscrimination provisions during the just-ended 100th
Congress.
   Would Bush use the power of the White House to push the issue in
Congress? she was asked.
   ``Sure,'' she said. ``That's the name of the game.''
   She said Bush and Dannemeyer have discussed the issue and ``do
disagree fairly heartily.''
   Steelman said confidentiality laws regarding AIDS testing need to
remain a matter for states, largely because they are so closely
linked to insurance regulation and other state functions.
   But since discrimination against people infected with the AIDS
virus _ or HIV _ is the ``down side'' to breached confidentiality,
she said, an overarching federal ban against such discrimination is
needed.
   Bush held a private dinner with Surgeon General C. Everett Koop
and National Institutes of Health AIDS chief Anthony Fauci a few
days before making a point on the campaign trail of backing the AIDS
commission's call for antidiscrimination legislation.
   Neither President Reagan, nor any other top White House official,
has taken such a position.
   The premise of public and private health officials in backing
strong antidiscrimination laws is that people likely to be carrying
the virus will not submit to the AIDS test for fear the results
would become public, and that that will make the epidemic harder to
track and fight.
   One of the commission's main criticisms of Reagan administration
health policies was that budget planning for AIDS research and
education was filtered through the normal bureaucratic process that
often results in requests originated by scientists being watered
down before they reach the White House.
   Asked about the stance a President Bush would take in dealing
with government health officials' requests for ammunition to fight
AIDS, Steelman said he ``probably will talk to them personally.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881102-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 1608EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Scotus-ChildAbuse     11-02 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Child Abuse,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Asked To Uphold Suits Against Social Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, hearing a case involving a
child beaten and crippled by his father, was told Wednesday that
suits against government social agencies are constitutional if
caseworkers fail to act to protect someone they know is in peril.
   Attorney Donald James Sullivan asked to court to uphold a suit by
the mother of nine-year-old Joshua DeShaney _ who was beaten so
severely by his father that he can only make awkward movements and
guttural sounds.
   Sullivan told the court that Winnebago County, Wis., social
welfare officials deprived the youth of his due process rights when
they ``refused to help the child'' five years ago, even while
knowing he was in ``immediate need of medical care.''
   The court, which took the case under advisement, was asked to
decide whether the Costitution permits suits against social agencies
for such alleged gross negligence.
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last year threw out the
suit by Melody DeShaney, of Cheyenne, Wyo., against the Winnebago
County Department of Social Services and two of its employees.
   Mark J. Mingo, representing the social agency, said the
Constitution would not support suits that subjected local
governments to ``massive new areas of exposure.''
   And he said that the job of social workers would be almost
impossible if they could be sued every time they make the wrong
decision.
   ``Social workers operate on the razor's edge,'' Mingo said.
``They must respond to the Constitutional right of parents in
management of their child.''
   He said a social worker ``must walk a fine line to prevent the
door from being slammed in her face to prevent future involvement.''
   Sullivan said he was not arguing the state has a ``broad
constitutional mandate to be all things to all people.''
   A government's ``affirmative constitutional duty,'' he said, came
only when there was ``extensive danger'' to the child and ``abundant
actual knowledge'' by the government _ knowledge he said was present
in this case.
   ``If the parents' rights are recognized, why should the rights of
the child be less recognized?'' he asked.
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor said it seemed Sullivan's argument
``would have a real deterrent effect'' on state agencies.
   Sullivan argued that ``It's okay'' for a social worker to ``guess
wrong.'' But he contended Joshua's caseworker was so keenly aware of
his danger that she once worried that she would pick up the phone
one day and learn the boy was dead.
   Asked by Justice John Paul Stevens, ``When did the constitutional
violation occur?'' Sullivan said it was when the agency allowed
Joshua to return home to his father after a three-day hospital stay
in 1983 for suspected child abuse.
   Mingo said the child went back because no hard evidence of abuse
was discovered, and the law required that the boy be sent home.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist told Sullivan, ``I don't see
how you turn around the limitations on the state to a duty on the
state.''
   The boy's father, Randy DeShaney, was convicted of felony battery
and child abuse and sentenced to two consecutive two-year prison
terms. He served about two years and eight months before he was
released in September 1987.
   Joshua remains in custody of the county and has no use of his
legs or one arm, and can only make awkward movements with one hand.
   The 7th circuit, in dismissing the suit, said, ``If the
defendants, though blameworthy, did not cause Joshua's injuries,
they cannot be said to have deprived him of his liberty.''
   The court said it was ``unlikely'' that the caseworker assigned
to Joshua did the boy ``any good at all. But it is most unlikely
that it did him any harm. She merely failed to protect him from his
bestial father.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881102-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 1919EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AsianPoor     11-02 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Asian Poor,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Food Foreseen for Hungry in Southeast Asia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About half the world's hungriest people _ 350
million of them _ live in India and Bangladesh, but 140 million of
them are on land with great promise of more farm production in the
1990s, a food policy official said Wednesday.
   John A. Mellor, director of the International Food Policy
Research Institute, said experts now know how to get more crops out
of the valleys of the Ganges and Brahmaputra rivers, where many of
the world's poorest and hungriest people are concentrated.
   ``Twenty years ago, it was premature to talk about eliminating
hunger and poverty in the world,'' Mellor, a former chief economist
for the U.S. Agency for International Development, told reporters.
``Now we have a base for doing it.''
   Mellor said it would be a long-term project _ 15 to 20 years _
based on developing improved varieties of grains and soybeans, as
well as better roads, bridges and other public works.
   Improving farming will have a multiplier effect on the growth of
incomes because farmers use most of their increased earnings in ways
that create more jobs, he said. ``The faster agriculture grows, the
faster its share of the economy declines,'' he explained.
   Mellor pointed to the example of the United States, where only 2
percent to 3 percent of the people are now in farming but production
of both food and industrial goods has increased tremendously since
the days when most Americans were farmers.
   To end poverty, people must get jobs in industry, he said.
   Mellor said farming in the Third World is dependent increasingly
on the market, and less on government control. Left-wing governments
help distribute land in the Third World but do not understand
farming, he said.
   ``Karl Marx was a city boy,'' Mellor explained.
   He calculated that of the 700 million undernourished people in
the world, 350 million live in Southeast Asia, 137 million in
Africa, 76 million in China, 72 million in Latin America, 34 million
in the Near East and 31 million in East Asia and the Pacific.
   Mellor's comments were based on a report he will deliver Friday
to the Consultative Group on International Agricultural Research, an
organization of 13 organizations coordinated by the World Bank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881102-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 1919EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChildAbuseDeaths     11-02 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Abuse Deaths,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Child-Abuse Deaths In Colorado Near Record For 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stepmother of a 5-year-old girl who choked to
death after allegedly being force-fed a ginger cake was held
Wednesday on $50,000 bail pending a hearing in the case.
   The death of Phenix Smith was Colorado's 19th reported
child-abuse fatality in 1988, one short of the record number
reported in 1982 and equaled in 1984 with two months to go in the
year.
   ``It's been a real bad year,'' said Jane Beveridge, administrator
of the state's child protection program.
   Phenix died in Children's Hospital on Saturday. Police reported
she apparently ``choked to death on a large amount of food'' and
also showed signs of possible sexual abuse.
   Phenix's stepmother, 31-year-old Beverly Smith, was accused of
force-feeding the girl as a punishment for sampling a ginger cake
without permission.
   The Adams County coroner performed an autopsy late Tuesday, but
District Attorney Jim Smith said results won't be released until
after charges are filed Thursday.
   Phenix's 12-year-old brother, 11-year-old stepsister and a
15-month-old half brother have been moved to foster homes.
   Statistics gathered by the National Committee for the Prevention
of Child Abuse in Chicago show that more children nationwide are
dying from abuse-related injuries.
   ``In 1987, we had more than 1,100 child abuse or neglect
fatalities,'' said Leslie Mitchel, an analyst with the national
organization. ``That's a 25 percent increase over 1985.''
   Mitchel said 30 percent to 60 percent of those deaths involve
cases that were known to child protection services before the deaths
occurred.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
