<DOCNO> AP881102-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 2012EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hirohito     11-02 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor Gets More Blood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito received a blood transfusion
Wednesday and palace officials said his condition was basically
unchanged, although he is weak and underweight.
   Hirohito, 87, received nearly a pint of blood to improve his
anemia, said Kenji Maeda, spokesman for the Imperial Household
Agency.
   Since Hirohito fell ill with internal bleeding Sept. 19, he has
received more than 34 pints of blood.
   Maeda said that by late afternoon, the emperor was running a
fever of 100.4, well above his normal reading of 95.9, but he said
Hirohito's condition remained stable.
   A senior palace official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the emperor's physical strength was waning and that he only
weighs about 88 pounds.
   He also said doctors were finding it difficult to locate new
veins to use for blood transfusions and intravenous feeding.
   Hirohito, the world's longest-reigning monarch, has eaten no
solid food since Sept. 19 except for a few spoons of weak porridge.
   Palace doctors have said he is bleeding internally in the upper
intestinal area, where physicians performed a bypass operation in
September 1987.
   The palace official also confirmed the emperor's situation was
critical over the weekend, when his blood pressure plummeted to 84
over 34. A healthy person's blood pressure is about 120 over 80.
   Hirohito received a visit Wednesday from his elder son, Crown
Prince Akihito, and Crown Princess Michiko and their son, Prince
Hiro, second in line to the throne. Other imperial family members
called on the emperor during the day.
   Akihito, 54, has taken over all imperial duties, including
signing government bills and receiving foreign envoys and visiting
dignitaries.
</TEXT>
