<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Yugoslavia     11-02 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Yugoslavia,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Says Yugoslavia Moving to More Democracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yugoslavia's leaders averted a civil war last
month and the country now faces prospects of less communism and more
democracy accompanied by painful economic adjustment, the president
of Slovenia, one of the nation's six republics, said Wednesday.
   ``Two weeks ago, you would have asked, `when does the civil war
come?'' but the crisis was defused by decisions taken in late
October by the national communist party's central committee, the
national assembly and others, said Janez Stanovnik.
   Stanovnik described recent developments to a National Press Club
gathering and later at a meeting with Secretary of State George
Shultz, a longtime acquaintance. He is on an unofficial visit to see
his son in Philadelphia and attend Friday's board meeting of the
International Management Institute in New York.
   Stanovik said demonstrations fueled by inflation and Serbian
nationalism were threatening decentralized Yugoslavia with civil war.
   The prospect of ethnic disturbances in the Republic of Bosnia, a
fragile community of Moslems, Christians and members of the Orthodox
faith prompted him and leaders of other republics to act through the
federal party on matters normally reserved to regional authorities,
he said.
   Stanovnik, a longtime leader of the ruling Yugoslav Communist
League and a contemporary of the late Marshall Josip Broz Tito, the
founder of modern Yugoslavia, said he realized that ``If this thing
will come to Bosnia and Bosnia disintegrated there will be
bloodshed. It was this that made me profoundly afraid we are truly
on the edge of civil war.''
   Stanovnik said he joined leaders of Montenegro and others at the
central committee to tell the Serbians ``please don't cross this
line ... which I thought we should in all friendship say to our
brothers.''
   The result was a non-confidence vote against Serbian politburo
member Dusan Ckrebic, widely regarded as a rebuff ``from the whole
of Yugoslavia'' to Serbian Communist Party chief Slobodan Milosevic
over fanning ethnic tensions, Stanovnik said.
   With this action, ``I think the whole situation in Yugoslavia has
changed and we have thus made a crucial start'' toward reform, he
said.
   Stanovnik said his differences with Milosevic were in political
strategy while in economic reform, ``Comrade Milosevic is as liberal
as I am.''
   Constitutional amendments subsequently approved by the national
assembly ``actually mean de-ideologizing the Yugoslav economy,''
with such changes as freeing private enterprise and business to
operate in a free market, said Stanovnik.
   The transformation carries essential political conditions, he
said, including human rights, free press, free expression, free
thought and, eventually, direct elections.
   Stanovnik said the Communist party, whose members make up only 10
percent of the population, ``must step down from directly
interfering in government affairs and must become rather a party of
movement and not of direct government.''
   This idea ``was by and large endorsed by the Yugoslav party,'' at
the recent central committee session, ``maybe not as a
enthusiastically as in Slovenia,'' but enough to warrant moderate
optimism for the future, he said.
   Stanovnik said the Slovenians also won adoption of their proposal
for reduced military spending on the premise that East-West detente
has revived. He gave no figures.
   Yugoslavia will have to cut social services and ``it will be very
painful,'' he said, because the country has been providing ``a
socialist heaven'' of good schools, hospitals and pensions without
producing enough to pay for them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
