<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PressProtest     11-02 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Press Protest,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Journalists in One-Day Strike Over IRA Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television journalists at the British Broadcasting
Corp. voted Wednesday to join a one-day strike protesting a
government ban on broadcasting interviews with members of the Irish
Republican Army.
   The Nov. 10 stoppage by the National Union of Journalists'
250-member branch at BBC Television Center could black out hourly
news bulletins and current affairs programs.
   The union, which called for the strike, said journalists at the
BBC World Service, the worldwide radio network, also will strike and
that BBC locals across Britain have voted overwhelmingly in favor of
protests ranging from partial stoppages to a full 24-hour walkout.
   Independent Television News, which is part of Britain's
commercial Independent Television network, will vote later in the
week on whether to strike. The 150-member ITN union local voted
unanimously against a strike at a meeting last week, the union said.
   ``The public should realise this has nothing to do with a defence
of terrorism,'' said John Foster, organizer for the estimated 4,000
television and radio journalists in the union. ``It is opposition to
a government attempt to censor broadcasting.''
   Broadcast journalists in Northern Ireland would not be asked to
strike because many of them feared the strike could be seen as
supporting terrorism, Foster said.
   On Oct. 20, the government of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
imposed an immediate ban on broadcast interviews with members of the
outlawed IRA and 10 other militant groups in Northern Ireland, and
their sympathizers.
   The ban was imposed under laws governing the two radio and TV
networks, the publicly financed BBC and the commercially funded
Independent Television.
   It followed an upsurge in killings by the mainly Roman Catholic
IRA, which is fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland and
unite the Protestant-dominated province with the Catholic Irish
Republic under socialist rule.
   Radio and television can still report in indirect speech the
views of members of the affected organizations and their supporters.
</TEXT>
