<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Pentagon-Ozone     11-02 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pentagon-Ozone,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Joins Battle To Replace Ozone-Damaging Chemicals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department, considered one of the
biggest U.S. offenders in its reliance on a chemical that depletes
the Earth's ozone layer, formally joined a government-industry task
force on Wednesday with a pledge to help find alternatives.
   The department, in a brief statement, said it would support a
three-step program aimed at finding and testing alternatives to
chlorofluorocarbon compounds or CFCs by April 1989.
   The task force is being led by the Environmental Protection
Agency but includes representatives of the major companies that
produce CFCs, electronics producers who rely heavily on the chemical
and various military agencies.
   One of the biggest uses of CFC compounds is as a solvent for
cleaning electronic components, circuit boards and materials that
are to be welded together. The compound also is used to clean metal
parts in a variety of weapon systems.
   ``In the United States in 1986, 150 million pounds of CFC-113
were used for prepping printed wire assemblies, metal cleaning and
precision cleaning,'' the Pentagon said.
   ``The armed forces and companies supplying equipment to them
accounted for nearly half of that, according to some estimates.''
   The Pentagon said the task force first would quantify the Defense
Department's cleanliness standards, then set up procedures for
testing and evaluating the effectiveness of alternative chemicals.
   Those first two phases ``will be completed early next year,'' the
Pentagon continued.
   The third and final phase will be the actual testing of
alternatives, ``and current plans are to complete testing of
alternative materials by April 1989,'' the statement said.
   The task force includes at least 23 corporations, including such
CFC producers as Du Pont and Allied-Signal; electronics' makers such
as the Digital Equipment Corp., AT&T and Magnavox, and such huge
defense contractors as General Dynamics, Honeywell, Hughes Aircraft,
IBM, Texas Instruments and Litton Industries, the Pentagon said.
   ``This program is a result of the Protocol on Substances that
Deplete the Ozone Layer, which was signed by the United States in
Montreal, Canada, last year,'' the Pentagon concluded.
   That protocol, or international treaty, contains a pledge by the
world's major producing nations to reduce by 50 percent their output
of CFCs by 1998.
   The ozone layer reduces the amount of cancer-causing ultraviolet
rays from the sun that reach the Earth's surface. The CFC compounds,
normally inert, rise through the atmosphere to the ozone layer,
where those same ultraviolet rays break them apart and free
ozone-destroying chlorine.
   According to scientific studies, the long-lived CFC compounds
have since about 1960 destroyed 2.5 percent of the ozone layer. The
EPA estimates that every percent decrease in ozone results in 43,000
additional skin cancer cases in the United States. Currently there
are about 500,000 cases a year.
   Besides their use as cleaning solvents, CFCs are used as
refrigeration fluids and plastic foam blowing agents. Many countries
still permit their use as aerosol propellants, a use banned in the
United States in 1978.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881102-0184 </DOCNO>
