<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CDC--AIDS-Colleges     11-02 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CDC--AIDS-Colleges,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Preliminary Results Suggest High AIDS Virus Infection On Campuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Preliminary results of a study of 20 U.S. colleges
suggest about three out of every thousand college students is
infected with the AIDS virus, according to federal health officials
who caution that final numbers may be either higher or lower.
   The national Centers for Disease Control, along with the American
College Health Association, is testing 1,000 anonymous blood samples
from each of 20 U.S. colleges as part of a family of surveys to
assess the prevalence of the AIDS virus in the U.S. population, CDC
spokeswoman Anne Simms said Wednesday.
   ``The survey is not expected to be completed until February
1989,'' she said. ``Until February, we really don't have any kind of
meaningful estimate of HIV (human immunodeficiency virus) infection
on college campuses.''
   About 5,000 of those samples have been tested, she said, showing
a rate of about three cases per 1,000 college students, or 0.3
percent. She said she did not know where the 5,000 samples came
from, whether they were from all 20 colleges in the study or just
some of them.
   ``This number was not unexpected,'' Ms. Simms said. ``We knew
that there was HIV infection among this population. This just
confirms what we already knew, and in fact the final results in
February may be higher or lower, we don't have any real way of
knowing.''
   By comparison, other studies indicate infection rates of four out
of 1,000 prisoners, or 0.4 percent.
   Nationwide, researchers believe the infection rate is between 0.4
percent and 0.6 percent, or perhaps 1.5 million people. The
government has estimated that 20 percent to 30 percent of those
infected with the AIDS virus will develop AIDS within five years,
although there are differing theories on this.
   CDC reported last week that 76,670 cases have been reported since
June 1981, with 43,027 fatalities.
   Some medical experts worry that most, if not virtually all, of
those infected with the virus will eventually become sick and die
because of evidence that the disease has a long incubation period.
   ``The only thing we can show from these preliminary results is
that there is HIV infection on college campuses. College students
are not immune from AIDS,'' Ms. Simms said.
   The preliminary results come on the heels of letter in September
from Assistant U.S. Secretary for Health Dr. Robert E. Windom to
university presidents and deans focusing on the danger to students.
   Windom said that one-fifth of the reported AIDS cases currently
occur among people 20 to 29 years old.
   ``Since the average incubation period (for AIDS) ... is seven
years or longer, it's clear that many of the 14,000 patients in this
group were high school or college age at the time of their
infection,'' Windom said in the letter.
   Ms. Simms said the preliminary results reinforce health
officials' advice that people engaging in high-risk behavior should
change their ways.
   AIDS is carried in blood and other bodily fluids and is most
commonly transmitted by sexual contact or by shared, contaminated
drug needles. Eighty-seven percent of all reported cases in the
United States have occurred among homosexual or bisexual males or
intravenous drug abusers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881102-0185 </DOCNO>
