<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Censor     11-02 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Censor,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chief Censor Says `Cult of Secrecy' Is Passing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's chief censor told Izvestia
Wednesday that the time of the ``cult of secrecy'' has passed, but
that his agency won't be disappearing from the lives of Soviet
journalists.
   The article in the government newspaper was Vladimir Boldirev's
first published interview.
   Boldirev, head of the Chief Directorate for the Protection of
Government Secrets in the Press, or Glavlit, said his country still
has secrets and any thought that his agency is no longer needed is
just ``a wish, not reality.''
   He said, however, that restrictions on the press have eased
considerably and that the list of banned topics has shrunk by a
third, Izvestia reported.
   Boldirev said that about 7,500 previously banned Soviet books
have been restored to library shelves, and most foreign publications
will soon join them.
   Glavlit still holds onto 400 Soviet books it considers
pornographic or likely to incite ethnic strife and these remain in
``special repositories,'' he said.
   The Soviet press now is allowed to report on many topics
previously banned, including major accidents, crime, and ecological
and medical problems, Boldirev noted. The media still are limited
when censors consider a report to contain state secrets or to be
prejudicial to Soviet interests.
   Also quick to earn the censor's denial are articles incompatible
with public morality and protection of health, and any that seem to
preach undermining or liquidating the socialist system, Boldirev
said.
   Censorship continues in other ways. Last week, authorities seized
typewriters, papers and other working materials of an unofficial
Leningrad weekly called Democratic Opposition, said Nikolai
Khamarov, an activist in Moscow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
