<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PTL     11-02 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latest PTL Bidder Would Bring Back Bakker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The latest bidder for PTL says it's
``absolutely necessary'' to return deposed evangelist Jim Bakker to
head the bankrupt ministry.
   Bakker responded Wednesday that he was ``thrilled at the
thought.''
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds is scheduled to choose a
buyer for PTL's assets Nov. 16 from four bids ranging from $113
million to $120 million for the Heritage USA complex, its 2,200
acres and the PTL television network.
   A group of ministers and businessmen calling themselves ``Lexalt
University'' offered $116 million for PTL last week. A spokesman for
the group said Tuesday that they want Bakker at the helm at Heritage
USA.
   Of the three previous bidders, one was recommended to Reynolds by
PTL Trustee M.C. ``Red'' Benton. In October, he recommended the
judge accept the $115 million offer from Stephen Mernick of Toronto.
After that, another Canadian, Vancouver's Peter Thomas of Samoth
Capital Corp., resubmitted a bid of $113 million directly to the
court.
   A bid of $120 million by a Christian business association called
``Holy Celebration'' was made Oct. 26. Its two trustees are Herbert
T. Nelson, a lawyer of Greenbelt, Md., and Sandi Kalez of Seattle.
   ``It's absolutely necessary,'' to give the ministry back to
Bakker, said the Rev. Edward J. Brown of Atlanta, who was acting for
``Lexalt University.''
   ``If Jim Bakker is not at the helm in the future, sooner or
later, Heritage USA would fall apart,'' Brown said Tuesday.
   ``I am thrilled at the thought of returning to television with
the people we love,'' Bakker said Wednesday. ``We're looking forward
to returning Heritage USA to the partners and lifetime members who
built it.''
   Brown offered $116 million in his bid in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in
Columbia. But ``Lexalt University does not really exist,'' said
Brown, an interdenominational minister and financial consultant.
   He said Lexalt University and The Covenant Group are names for
the ``facilitators,'' the financial backers who will ``bring the
funds.''
   Lexalt backers are ``ministers who are teachers. There will be an
opportunity to teach'' at Heritage USA if it's sold to Lexalt, he
said.
   The Covenant Group describes itself as ``Christian businessmen
and associates of men all over the country, in and out of the United
States.''
   Brown said he has been a minister 17 years, but has been in a
traveling ministry since he resigned from his congregation in
Redding, Calif., in 1984. He had been an Assemblies of God minister,
he said.
   Bakker left the ministry amid a sex and money scandal in March
1987. Three months later, PTL filed for protection from its
creditors in bankruptcy court.
</TEXT>
