<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Panama-Soviets     11-02 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Soviets,175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Promise to Respect Canal Neutrality</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union turned over to the
Organization of American States on Wednesday a document pledging
Soviet respect for the neutrality of the Panama Canal when the
waterway comes under Panamanian control at the end of the century.
   Soviet Ambassador Yuri Dubinin, speaking in Spanish, said the
pledge applies ``both to peacetime and to wartime as well.''
   A protocol attached to the Panama Canal treaties is designed to
ensure the neutrality of the canal, and 36 nations have promised to
abide by that provision.
   OAS Secretary General Joao Baena Soares said the Soviet step was
a ``clear demonstration'' of Soviet willingness to contribute to the
rule of law.
   Panamanian OAS delegate Soraya Cano noted that U.S.-Panamanian
relations have been tense for some time but that her government
believes that issues related to the canal should not be affected.
   William Price, a member of the U.S. delegation to the OAS, said
that in the next 11 years, the United States will continue working
with Panama to carry out the terms of the treaties.
</TEXT>
