<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan     11-02 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Disperse Rioters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Wednesday used tear gas and
batons to disperse thousands of rioting young people who shouted
``No sugar, no bread!'' and ``Down with the dictators,'' witnesses
said.
   It was the fifth straight day of protests against high food
prices and the government of Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi. Officials
reported several arrests but no casualties.
   Khartoum Commissioner Fatih Abdoun told the protesters the
government would do its best to ease shortages of bread and sugar.
   Moslem fundamentalists and university students joined the
demonstrations, which ended by mid-afternoon. Many protesters had to
walk home under a burning sun because the disturbances shut down
public bus service.
   The city center was almost deserted, except for riot police who
continued to patrol streets littered with ashes from burned tires.
   High school students began protesting last Saturday, throwing
stones and burning tires in the streets of Khartoum and Omdurman,
the capital's twin city across the Nile River.
   On Tuesday, riot police fired into the air to disperse youths who
attacked several government installations, including Khartoum's main
local government building and the Cabinet offices.
   The newspaper Al-Sudani reported that shots also were fired
Tuesday to disperse stone-throwers at the U.S. Embassy. Riot police
on Wednesday sealed off roads leading to the embassy and various
government ministries.
   Schools and universities have not been closed officially, but
many were shuttered out of fear that demonstrators would attack
students who were not participating.
   In 1985, 10 days of riots against high food prices led to a
general strike that ended the 16-year dictatorship of former
President Gaafar Nimeiri. Those protests were led by professionals
and unionists, however, and the current disturbances appear to have
involved only young people.
   Mahdi was elected prime minister in 1986. His government faces
severe economic problems, including an $11-billion foreign debt and
70 percent inflation.
</TEXT>
