<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WhoopingCough     11-02 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Whooping Cough,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whooping Cough Claims Amish Infant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CONEWANGO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An outbreak of whooping cough among rural
Amish who refuse vaccinations against the disease has claimed one
infant and may threaten the lives of several other children, health
officials said Wednesday.
   The death of a four-month-old boy Monday in the Cattaraugus
County town of Conewango is the first U.S. whooping cough fatality
in three years, federal health officials said.
   Six other Amish children have been diagnosed with the disease,
according to Dr. James Wild, director of the Conewango Valley
Medical Center.
   The same community was hit by 216 cases of the disease in 1982
and six cases were reported in 1985, officials said. There were no
deaths from the previous outbreaks.
   Conewango is about 45 miles south of Buffalo and is home to about
1,200 Amish, members of a strict Mennonite sect that shuns modern
conveniences.
   ``The Amish are a very closed society and they resist modern
ways. Most of them just don't believe in immunizations, they don't
think they are necessary,'' said Patricia Kota, a registered nurse
and assistant administrator of Tri-County Hospital in Gowanda.
   Whooping cough, or pertussis, is a respiratory disease that
causes a chronic cough, vomiting and a characteristic ``whoop'' when
the victim gasps for air.
   Among adults and older children it can seem to be little more
than a cold, but it can be fatal for infants and small children,
according to officials at the federal Centers for Disease Control in
Atlanta, Ga.
   The country's most recent whooping cough outbreak affected about
100 children last year in an Amish settlement in Delaware, said
Kenneth Allman, spokesman for the disease control agency.
   Most children are protected against whooping cough by the ``DPT''
series of immunizations, but most Amish children do not get
immunized, officials said.
   Immunization is required of all public school children in New
York unless there are extenuating religious or health reasons.
   ``Once the disease gets a foothold in this type of community it
can take off quickly,'' said William Fagel, a spokesman for the
state Health Department.
</TEXT>
