<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Denies Stay of Execution for Texas Murderer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court denied a stay of execution
Wednesday for a Texas man convicted in the 1975 slaying of a nurse,
clearing the way for his death by injection early Thursday, a court
spokeswoman said.
   Donald Gene Franklin's application was referred to the full court
by Justice Byron R. White, and the court decided 7-2 to deny the
application, said spokeswoman Toni House. Justices Thurgood Marshall
and William J. Brennan Jr. issued their standard dissent, she said.
   Franklin, who was once described by his own attorney as the most
hated man in San Antonio, was convicted in the July 1975 death of
Mary Margaret ``Peggy'' Moran.
   Ms. Moran disappeared from a San Antonio hospital and was found
five days later, barely alive, in a vacant lot. Nude and bleeding
from multiple stab wounds, she died later in a hospital.
   Franklin, who was on parole for a rape conviction when he was
arrested, consistently denied any involvement in Ms. Moran's death
and blamed it on a friend.
</TEXT>
