<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 1826EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-HousingTenants     11-02 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Housing Tenants,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Enjoined From Changing Public Housing Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration on Wednesday was
enjoined temporarily from restricting grievance procedures that
advocates contend protect the rights of 3.4 million Americans living
in public housing.
   U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt issued a temporary restraining
order that bars the Department of Housing and Urban Development from
implementing new regulations that had been set to take effect on
Monday.
   Pratt, who scheduled further proceedings on Nov. 22, said
tenants' organizations that sued HUD had raised ``some valid
complaints'' about the elimination of many longstanding grievance
procedures for tenants to contest eviction or complain about
substandard living conditions.
   ``Tenants would be stripped of their rights'' to grievance
proceedings to contest evictions or to force local housing
authorities to provide heat and make repairs, said Florence Roisman,
a staff attorney for the National Housing Law Project.
   Ms. Roisman argued that HUD was flouting the intent of Congress
by effectively repealing longstanding regulations that had been
pieced together by legislation and a series of court decisions.
   According to the plaintiffs' complaint, only people whose
signatures appear on public housing leases would have a right to a
grievance hearing under the new regulation.
   The new regulations also would eliminate pre-eviction hearings
before local housing authorities. Such hearings would take place in
state courts. The regulations also would narrow the category of
issues that can be raised in grievance proceedings.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney William J. Dempster said HUD was trying
to ``take long overdue action to deregulate what has been a
ponderous and Byzantine centralized regulatory process.''
   ``The current regulations ... have straitjacketed public housing
authorities and rendered them virtually unable to deal with the
problems they are facing,'' Dempster said.
   The regulations would only be interim because Congress passed
legislation, expected to be signed into law by President Reagan,
that requires the department to continue to review them.
   The judge expressed some sympathy for HUD's position, saying:
``The public housing program has not been a smashing success. It has
been inordinately expensive.''
   ``Some of the regulations make a lot of sense to me,'' said
Pratt, noting he once chaired a public housing authority in suburban
Montgomery County, Md. ``On the other hand, I think she's (Ms.
Roisman) got some valid complaints,'' the judge told Dempster.
   ``Some of the regulations make a lot of sense to me,'' Pratt told
Dempster. ``On the other hand, I think she's (Ms. Roisman) got some
valid complaints.''
   Ms. Roisman pointed to a congressional report that said
``Congress is seriously concerned that the recent regulations would
weaken principles of fairness and due process that have been
painstakingly developed over 20 years as a result of legislative and
judicial actions.''
   The report from a House-Senate conference committee said it was
``particularly dismayed'' that HUD had ignored instructions in
legislation to redraft the regulations to conform with a 1985 court
decision. That ruling found that Congress intended to require
grievance proceedings when a public housing agency refuses to make
repairs or provide decent conditions.
   ``We think the regulation that we published does precisely what
Congress intended,'' HUD attorney Steven Baylis said.
   Baylis said in a telephone interview that HUD intended to make it
easier to evict tenants who commit crimes.
   ``If somebody in the family mugs another tenant it makes good
common sense there should be a way to evict the family.''
   Ms. Roisman contended that current regulations give authorities
enough power to evict criminals without denying tenants due process.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
