<1ST_LINE>u a AM-OfficialEnglish     11-02 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Official English,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Joins Court Challenge to Official English
Measure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department on Wednesday joined a group
opposing the official English initiative on the Florida ballot,
arguing that petitions for the measure violated federal voting
rights law.
   Last week U.S. District James W. Kehoe threw out a suit seeking
to stop the initiative, but a special panel of federal judges is to
consider an appeal of his decision at a hearing Thursday.
   The Justice Department's legal brief supports the effort to stop
Amendment 11, which would make English the state's official language.
   ``We think it's fantastic _ maybe the best news I've heard in the
campaign,'' said Jon Weber, executive director of Speak Up Now,
which filed suit against the initiative on behalf of four
Spanish-speaking residents.
   ``It shows we were right on the law,'' he said. ``The Justice
Department does not get involved in suits of this nature and lose. ''
   Opponents have argued that petitions for the initiative should
have been circulated in Spanish as well as English in six heavily
Hispanic Florida counties.
   Florida English, the group that collected more than 500,000
signatures to put the initiative on Tuesday's ballot, successfully
argued before Kehoe that the petitions were private, not public, and
therefore not covered under the federal Voting Rights Act. A federal
appeals court had made a similar ruling in a Colorado case.
   The Justice Department is opposing those rulings in what Weber
says is the first time the federal government has entered the
official English controversy.
   ``They reject the argument that the petition process is
private,'' Weber said. ``They say the state is clearly involved
throughout the petition process, and that the election itself is
merely the culmination of that process.''
   Florida English Chairman Mark LaPorta reacted angrily to news of
the Justice Department's intervention.
   ``I'm offended that they're involved,'' LaPorta said. ``What
they're doing is a last ditch effort based on a glitch, a
technicality.''
   He said it would not change the group's efforts, which the latest
polls show is likely to receive the support of 70 percent of
Florida's voters.
</TEXT>
