<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen 2ndLd-Writethru a0747 11-02 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0747,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede NORTH CANTON, Ohio</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bentsen Seeks Votes in Midwest Criticizing Quayle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with appearance in Charleston, INSERT two grafs
after 11th pvs, Arriving in...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MASSILLON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen stumped through the industrial heartland on Wednesday,
shaking hands with blue-collar workers and carrying Michael Dukakis'
message of economic nationalism and middle-class squeeze.
   ``We're on your side in this fight, middle-class America,'' the
Texas senator told a hard-hatted crowd at the LTV cold steel
finishing plant in Massillon.
   The steel industry has been hard hit by foreign competition, and
Bentsen touted his experience in trade when when speaking to the
employees.
   ``What you need is someone who'll stand up for the workers of
America,'' he said. ``Export the products and not the jobs.''
   Bentsen donned a yellow hard hat and toured part of the plant,
near Canton, Ohio, which employees 350 people. After visiting a work
station where steel rods are finished and packaged, he stuck a
``USA'' label on a bundle.
   ``I'll stand American workers against any workers in the world,''
he said. When Bush became vice president, Americans were the highest
paid workers in the world, he said. Now, he said, they trailed
behind the Japanese and West Germans, he said.
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, said it was time to vote Democratic
because the Republicans weren't doing enough to help industries hurt
by unfair trade.
   ``They've talked like Rambo and they've acted like Bambi,'' he
said.
   Bentsen also continued his attacks on Bush's running mate, Dan
Quayle.
   ``I'd like to have George Bush here and ask him ... did you pick
the very best person?'' he said.
   Arriving in Ohio, Bentsen was greeted at the Akron-Canton airport
by a boisterous crowd of several hundred supporters in a hangar on a
cold, drizzly day.
   From Ohio, Bentsen traveled to Charleston, W.Va., where he
attended a rally with Senate Majoriy Leader Robert C. Byrd and
Senate colleague John D. Rockefeller, along with other West Virginia
elected officials.
   Rep. Bob Wise clogged to get the crowd stirred up, and a band
played ``la Bamba'' and ``Signed, Sealed, Delivered, I'm Lloyd,'' a
variation on a Motown song.
   Bentsen started the day at Southern Illinois University in
Carbondale, where he told supporters that Bush's choice of Quayle
``showed a real disdain, disregard for our country.''
   Several times in his speech, Bentsen called the Republican vice
presidential nominee ``R. Dan Quayle,'' getting wrong the
candidate's first initial, which is J.
   He criticized Quayle for his positions on issues including 60
days' advance notice for plant closings.
   The Democratic vice presidential nominee was introduced by
Illinois' two senators, Democrats Paul Simon and Alan Dixon.
   Simon launched the attack on Quayle, saying that if Republicans
in the U.S. Senate were polled as to whether they preferred Bentsen
or Quayle, Bentsen would win handily. ``It would be a washaway,'' he
said.
   He told the crowd ``Don't believe the polls,'' a message Bentsen
has been delivering in the final push of his campaign as he insists
the Democrats are staging a comback that will put them over the top
on Election Day.
   Tad Devine, a top aide to Dukakis who coordinates Bentsen's
campaign with that of the Massachusetts governor, said there was
evidence in Democratic polling that Quayle was increasing as an
issue, and he said that could be critical in close states such as
Ohio and Illinois.
   Devine said the campaign was seeking maximum television exposure
for Bentsen in the last few days of the campaign to highlight the
differences between him and Quayle.
   ``George Bush said, judge me by how I pick my vice presidential
candidate,'' Bentsen said Wednesday.
   Also Wednesday, a Federal Aviation Administration inspector was
flying in Bentsen's campaign jet. The agency received a letter,
illegibly signed, alleging lax safety procedures on the plane.
</TEXT>
