<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Mehta,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philharmonic Director Leaving in 3 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zubin Mehta, music director of the New York
Philharmonic since 1978, said Wednesday he will leave his post to
pursue ``other artistic endeavors'' when his contract expires in
three seasons.
   Mehta, music director of the Montreal and Los Angeles orchestras
before moving here, said he was turning down a contract extension in
order to free himself of the administrative responsibilities of the
position.
   He announced his decision to the 106-member orchestra Wednesday
morning, after pondering his contract renewal for several months.
   ``The search for a successor will begin shortly,'' said Stephen
Stamas, president of the orchestra corporation. Stamas said in a
statement that he regretted Mehta's decision not to renew.
   As music director, Mehta is responsible for the artistic
administration of the orchestra _ auditioning and hiring players,
selecting works, planning tours and broadcasts and conducting
rehearsals and performances.
   Mehta, 52, said in a statement: ``Having held the position of
music director with various North American orchestras since 1961, I
must at this juncture pursue other artistic endeavors which have to
do with less administrative activity than that with which a music
director is usually involved.''
   Mehta is also music director for life of the Israel Philharmonic.
</TEXT>
