<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Anglo-IrishAccord     11-02 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anglo-Irish Accord,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British, Irish Govts To Review Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British and Irish
governments said Wednesday they will carry out a major review of a
1985 pact that gives the Irish Republic an advisory voice in
British-ruled Northern Ireland.
   A review after three years was part of the Anglo-Irish Agreement
when it was signed Nov. 15, 1985, by Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher of Britain and Prime Minister Garret FitzGerald of Ireland.
   The accord was intended to give Northern Ireland's Roman Catholic
minority more confidence in the administration of the
Protestant-majority province. Catholics say the courts and
employment in the province still are biased against them.
   The review was announced jointly in Belfast Wednesday by Tom
King, Britain's top official in Northern Ireland, and Irish Foreign
Affairs Minister Brian Lenihan.
   A joint communique said the review would be aimed at developing a
positive program for the future of Northern Ireland.
   Progress on combating the outlawed Irish Republican Army's
violent struggle against British rule was discussed at a separate
meeting between law ministers and police chiefs. No details were
disclosed but officials indicated cooperation on both sides of the
border was better than it had been for several years.
   Northern Ireland's Protestant politicians, who bitterly oppose
the 1985 pact, rejected an invitation from King to join talks on the
review. Officials said senior Protestant churchmen and leading
businessmen would likely be invited to meet King.
</TEXT>
