<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Reynolds     11-02 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Reynolds,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burt Reynolds Shows To Bring Money To Palm Beach County</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUPITER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sometimes when a local boy makes good, he
wants his hometown to make out like a bandit, and happily for Palm
Beach County, actor Burt Reynolds is one of those successes.
   Reynolds plans to return to prime-time television in ``B.L.
Stryker,'' a series of six two-hour episodes set in the county. With
each of the episodes budgeted at $4 million, the local economy could
get a hefty infusion.
   Reynolds, a native of the county, plays a Vietnam veteran and
retired New Orleans vice cop who returns to his home in West Palm
Beach. He and Tom Selleck, late of ``Magnum, p.i.,'' are the
executive producers.
   Each of the episodes will be shot on location around the county
in the next six months, Reynolds said Tuesday.
   ``We hope to leave a lot of that (the series' budget) here,'' he
said. ``There are an enormous amount of vehicles that we have to
lease, there's always greenery you have to get, there's furniture
you have to rent. ... The list goes on and on.
   ``Anything that we can get in Palm Beach County, we'll ask here
first before we look somewhere else,'' he said.
   ``This is a very big deal here in Jupiter,'' Mayor Mary Hinton
said. ``We know what a tremendous economic impact it will be. This
show could very easily be one of the largest employers we have in
the town of Jupiter.''
   Not everyone is thrilled at the return of a favorite son.
   The tony resort town of Palm Beach didn't want its police station
used as a primary set, so the Boca Raton station will be used
instead, according to co-producer Alan Barnette of Blue Period
Productions.
   Reynolds' previous efforts to work in the county were rebuffed;
when he sought to film ``The Longest Yard'' at Union Correctional
Institution at Raiford, he was turned down because the film
contained four-letter words, he said. The film about a Florida
convict was shot in Georgia.
</TEXT>
