<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Northrop-Stealth     11-02 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northrop-Stealth,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Won't Join Suit Alleging Northrop Fraud on B-2 Bomber</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department announced Wednesday that
it will stay out of a private suit by four Northrop Corp. employees
alleging the company defrauded the government in the production of
the B-2 Stealth bomber.
   Assistant Attorney General John Bolton, head of the Justice
Department's civil division, said in a statement that after a review
and investigation of the allegations, ``the Department has decided
that there is not a sufficient basis for it to enter the case at
this time.''
   The lawsuit says Northrop's Advance Systems Division falsely
represented to the government that its cost schedule control system
met contractual requirements and that Northrop submitted falsified
reports on cost performance and other matters.
   The suit, which was filed last February in U.S. District Court in
Los Angeles by a current Northrop employee, Terrence Schielke, and
three former Northrop workers, also alleges labor mischarging and
mischarging on sales orders and said the company charged the
government for idle time of its employees.
   Northrop has denied the accusations.
   The Baltimore Sun in a story last week quoted congressional
sources as saying the Justice Department won't take over the lawsuit
because some Air Force personnel overlooked irregularities to keep
development of the classified project moving ahead.
   A Justice Department spokeswoman, Amy Brown, declined to provide
any details on why the government isn't joining the private suit.
   The Justice Department could enter the private suit later on a
showing of good cause.
   Meanwhile, the U.S. attorney's office in Los Angeles is
conducting a criminal investigation of Northrop's work on the
bomber, which is due to be unveiled on Nov. 22.
   The B-2 is to be operational in the early 1990s and Congress has
authorized the purchase of 132 of the bombers, which are built with
materials designed to make the aircraft less visible to enemy radar.
The total estimated cost for the planes is $36.6 billion.
</TEXT>
