<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-02 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Whitens Upstate New York, Vermont, With Indian Summer
Elsewhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy snow Wednesday blanketed parts of northeastern New York and
northern Vermont, and showers dampened the northern parts of both
coasts, but it was a pleasant Indian summer day across the nation's
midsection.
   Cold air pulled by a low pressure system brought snow to upstate
New York, with 11 inches recorded at Malone, about 15 miles south of
the Quebec border. In Schoharie County, west of Albany, 5 inches of
snow fell at Broome Center. In Vermont, 8 inches was measured at
Brandon Gap, Jay Peak and near Hancock.
   Rain was scattered over parts of the southern New England and
mid-Atlantic coast as well as over eastern Ohio and western
Pennsylvania.
   A cold front spread rain, accompanied by strong winds, across the
northern Pacific coast. Winds gusted to 60 mph at Astoria, Ore., and
high wind wanings were posted for the southern Washington and
northern Oregon coast, where gusts could reach 70 mph, the National
Weather Service said. Farther inland, rainshowers developed over
parts of Wyoming.
   The center of the nation enjoyed mostly sunny skies with some
high clouds drifting across the Mississippi Valley and western
Texas. Temperatures were in the 70s from Texas and the lower
Mississippi Valley into the central High Plains.
   Afternoon temperatures reached the 60s or 70s across much of the
nation, but it was chillier across the northern tier, with the
mercury in the 30s and 40s from the upper Mississippi Valley through
the Great Lakes and upper Ohio Valley into New England. Temperatures
were in the 50s from the Pacific Northwest across the northern
Rockies and from eastern Dakotas into parts of the lower Ohio Valley
and the mid-Atlantic states. Southern Florida, parts of the Rio
Grande Valley and southwestern Arizona basked in 80-degree warmth.
   The low in the nation early Wednesday was 10 degrees at Gunnison,
Colo.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 32
degrees at Saranac Lake, N.Y., to 84 degrees at McAllen, Texas.
   For Thursday, the forecast called for widespread showers across
the northern Pacific coast eastward to the Rockies, and snowshowers
scattered across northern Maine. Highs were predicted in the 60s or
70s across much of the nation, but in the 50s in the Northwest and
from the northern Plains across the Great Lakes and upper Ohio
Valley to southern New England. Central New England was expected to
have temperatures in the 40s, with the mercury only reaching the 30s
in the northern part of the region. Southern Florida, the western
Gulf Coast, much of the southern Plains and southern Plateau and
desert Southwest were expected to have highs in the 80s, and
temperatures in the low 90s were forecast for the Rio Grande Valley
and southwest Arizona.
</TEXT>
