<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Reagan 2ndLd-Writethru a0761 11-02 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0761,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Democrats Want Voters' Wallets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with `Roger Rabbit'' quote, INSERT one graf after
8th pvs, ``The truth...''
^By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEREA, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan derided Michael Dukakis'
``I'm on your side'' appeal to Midwestern voters on Wednesday,
saying Democrats ``are on your side when they want to get their
hands on your wallets.''
   Reagan pushed Vice President George Bush's cause _ and campaigned
on behalf of two GOP Senate candidates _ with fund-raising
appearances in the Cleveland suburb of Berea and in Milwaukee on the
last leg of a week-long, cross-country campaign swing.
   Aides said he will be out again in four more battleground states
in the waning days of the presidential campaign. Reagan will travel
to Chicago and to southern New Jersey on Friday, and make a rare
Saturday trip with stops in Michigan and Dallas.
   The president, obviously buoyed by his vice president's lead in
national polls, told audiences, ``Come next week, the American
public will say no to liberals.''
   ``Come next week, the American public will say no to the
Massachusetts liberal who preaches higher taxes, big spending and a
weak defense,'' Reagan said.
   Speaking to a GOP rally at Baldwin-Wallace College, Reagan
pursued with gusto his bashing of Bush's Democratic opponent,
portraying him as out of touch with mainstream American voters.
   ``You know, the liberals are going around saying they're on your
side. You know better than that,'' Reagan said. ``Our side believes
people who want to protect their home and family from an armed
intruder have a constitutional right to own a gun. The liberals are
against it.''
   ``The truth is, they only come around on your side when they want
to get their hands on your wallets,'' Reagan said. ``I remember the
last time the American people heard that kind of talk, in 1980, the
American people let them know they weren't on your side, they were
on your back.''
   Reagan scoffed at Dukakis' claims to being a Democrat in the
Harry Truman mold, saying, ``I'll tell you one thing, if he's Harry
Truman I'm Roger Rabbit.''
   Without naming him, Reagan took aim at 71-year-old Sen. Howard
Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, who is being challenged by Cleveland Mayor
George Voinovich, a 52-year-old Republican who has won three
landslide mayoral victories in his strongly Democratic city.
   As he had in a previous campaign stop in the state last month,
Reagan said of Metzenbaum, ``He's liberal, liberal, liberal.'' He
said Voinovich had ``saved the city of Cleveland'' from financial
straits.
   Recent polling has shown Metzenbaum well ahead.
   With a morning stop in Milwaukee, Reagan followed in the
footsteps of both Bush and Dukakis, who'd campaigned there Tuesday.
   He told voters to reject ``far-out liberalism'' when they cast
their ballots for president and Congress.
   Speaking at a $150-per-person brunch for Republican senatorial
candidate Susan Engeleiter, the president noted that Dukakis has
recently said he is a liberal in the tradition of presidents
Roosevelt, Truman and Kennedy.
   ``My friends, we are making some progress. After all of these
months, and all of this time, George's opponent has finally come out
of the closet. He has finally embraced the L-word,'' Reagan said.
   Reagan said Mrs. Engeleiter ``stands with George Bush, and her
opponent stands with a certain liberal tank driver.'' Dukakis rode
in a tank during a stop in Sterling Heights, Mich., a photo that has
been used against him in Bush commercials.
   Mrs. Engeleiter is running against Democrat Herbert Kohl for the
seat of Sen. William Proxmire, who is retiring after 31 years in the
Senate.
   ``I believe the Senate could use a mother's perspective, as
well,'' Reagan said.
   After delivering his speech in Ohio, the president drove to a
nearby training field for the Cleveland Browns football team where
he reminisced with the players about his days as a right guard on
his college team and as a radio sports announcer.
   Reagan spoke of missing a block as a player but later,
auditioning for a radio station, recreating it so that he
``delivered a block that was earth shattering.''
   The president hurled the pigskin at tight end Ozzie Newsome and
also threw a pass to Ricky Bolden, an offensive tackle.
   Reagan, queried as to whether his week-long campaign swing for
Bush had done the presidential candidate any good, said, ``I've
tried _ only time will tell.''
</TEXT>
