<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ThalidomideDoctor     11-02 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thalidomide Doctor,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thalidomide Doctor Found Guilty of Scientific Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Australian gynecologist William McBride,
who alerted the world to the dangers of the drug thalidomide on
human fetuses in the 1960s, was found guilty of scientific fraud
Wednesday.
   An independent inquiry headed by former High Court Chief Justice
Sir Harry Gibbs found that McBride deliberately falsified the
results of a 1980 experiment on rabbits involving birth defects.
   McBride, 61, immediately resigned as head of research at the
Sydney-based Foundation 41, which he started in 1971 to research
birth defects. The institution was financed by the proceeds of
international awards for his work on thalidomide.
   About 8,000 babies were born around the world with severe
deformities attributed to thalidomide, a sedative administered to
pregnant women, until McBride's findings led to its banning.
   McBride issued a statement through lawyers protesting his
innocence, saying: ``I reject absolutely the finding that scientific
fraud occurred in connection with the experiment.''
   It said he resigned ``because I don't wish that there be any
doubt cast over the work that I and the Foundation have done over
the past 16 years''.
   The foundation's board called the inquiry after pressure from the
scientific community about fraud allegations by two former research
assistants, broadcast on an Australian Broadcasting Corp. radio
program last December.
   Researchers Phil Vardy and Jill French said that McBride reported
in a 1982 edition of the Australian Journal of Biological Sciences
that two of eight rabbits given the drug Scopolamine Hydrobromide
produced deformed fetuses.
   Vardy and French claimed that in fact only one of six rabbits
produced deformed offspring, that a dosage table was altered and
that the article falsely reported that fetuses were sectioned and
control rabbits were kept.
   Gibbs and two medical researchers began hearing evidence in
secret in July.
   In a 25-page report released late Wednesday, they supported the
allegations and found that McBride ``deliberately falsified'' the
contents of the article.
   ``The experiment mentioned in that paper was not conducted in
accordance with proper scientific method and was not honestly
reported,'' they found.
   ``The above experiment and its published results does suggest
that in relation to the publication of those results Dr. McBride was
lacking in scientific integrity.''
   The report said McBride claimed in evidence that a drug company
was out to destroy his credibility as a witness in legal action by
users of a morning sickness drug. But it said no evidence of bias
was found among the witnesses against him.
   Foundation 41's board said in a statement it accepted McBride's
resignation as honorary medical director of the foundation ``with
regret'' and appreciated his offer to continue to serve while a
replacement was found.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881102-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 1902EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HospitalKidnapping     11-02 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital Kidnapping,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premature Baby Snatched From Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELISSA CONTI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A premature baby who was kidnapped from
a hospital by a woman posing as a nurse could die without proper
treatment, authorities said Wednesday.
   Christopher Michael Jones, who was six weeks premature when born
Saturday at Doctors Hospital, was taken from his mother Tuesday
night.
   On Wednesday, at a news conference, Annette Jones-Thomas pleaded
for her baby's return.
   ``Please, if you have my child, please return him,'' Mrs.
Jones-Thomas said. ``He needs medical attention and if you have him
for the reason of taking him as your child and raising him and
loving him, do what a good mother would do. Bring him to the
hospital and let him get help.''
   The baby weighed only four pounds and must be fed every three
hours because he is small, Dr. Whit Hall said. The doctor said the
infant also must be kept warm.
   ``The baby's blood sugar can get very low and we were watching it
carefully in the hospital. If it gets too low it can cause seizures
or even death within a relatively short period of time,'' Hall said.
   The child was taken from Mrs. Jones-Thomas in her fourth-floor
room just after 10 p.m. Tuesday by a woman who was dressed in a
white pleated skirt and a white sweater, police and hospital
officials reported.
   Mrs. Jones-Thomas, 32, who appeared at the news conference with
her husband, Willie Jones, 39, said she did not know the kidnapper.
She described the woman as black, about 20 years old, 5-foot-4, 135
pounds, with black shoulder-length hair.
   The woman said she needed to weigh the baby, Mrs. Jones-Thomas
said.
   The ruse was discovered about 30 minutes later, when a nurse came
into the room to take the baby to the nursery, officials said.
   Police were contacted shortly after 11 p.m. and searched the area
with dogs but found nothing.
   Mrs. Jones-Thomas said the baby has black straight hair and a
reddish tint to his face. He also has a growth on his right ear.
   Doctors Hospital offered a $10,000 reward for the return of the
baby, the Little Rock Childrens Clinic offered $1,000 and Protecting
Arkansas Children Together added another $1,000.
   Geri Frances Vaughters, a hospital technician, said she saw a
woman fitting the description of the kidnapper before the incident.
Ms. Vaughters said she thought the woman was a visitor.
   Security at the hospital remains the same, but spokeswoman
Jessica Szenher said patients have been warned to ask for
identification from anyone entering their rooms.
   The kidnapper was not wearing a nurses' identification tag, Ms.
Szenher said. Police Sgt. Larry Dunnington said authorities didn't
know how the woman entered or left the hospital.
   There are 20 entrances to the hospital and all but four were
locked at 9:15 p.m., according to security records.
   Dunnington said he believes the kidnapper is still in the state,
but declined to elaborate. He said the Little Rock police department
has nearly 20 detectives working on the case.
   Dr. Terry Jefferson, one of the Jones' pediatricians, said of the
kidnapping, ``You don't think of it happening in Little Rock ...
more in New York or California.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881102-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 2216EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PlaneCrash     11-02 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plane Crash,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three FAA Workers Die As Jet Crashes, Burns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIGONIER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jet plane that apparently lost power
crashed in the foothills of the Allegheny Mountains on Wednesday,
killing all three Federal Aviation Administration employees aboard,
officials said.
   FAA spokesmen said the three were making a routine check of a
Pennsylvania airport's instrument landing system.
   The pilot told the FAA's Cleveland Flight Center about a ``power
problem'' just before the crash, said FAA spokesman Pete Nelson.
   The pilot's precise words, which were recorded, were not
immediately available, Nelson said.
   The crash occurred in a wooded area about 45 miles east of
Pittsburgh.
   FAA officials said the victims were pilot James E. Burger, 64, of
Linwood, N.J.; co-pilot Richard M. Wadsworth, 46, of Ocean City,
N.J.; and technician Theodore L. Burdick, 56, of Egg Harbor
Township, N.J.
   Burger had 17,000 hours of flight time, said FAA spokeswoman
Holly Baker.
   The National Transportation Safety Board began an investigation
into the accident.
   The twin-engine plane took off from Allegheny County Airport on
Wednesday morning to test the electronic signal emitted from an
instrument landing system, an FAA official said.
</TEXT>
