<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland-Thatcher 1stLd-Writethru a0663 11-02 0841</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Thatcher, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,0864</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Sees Similarities Between Her Choices and Poland's</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 19 grafs UPDATING with Thatcher comment, other
detail; PICKS up 13th pvs `She also is ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain
told the Polish premier Wednesday she sees similarities between
changes she has made in Britain and the difficult choices facing
Poland, a British official said.
   He said Mrs. Thatcher, who turned Britain away from socialism,
told Premier Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski of this troubled communist
nation: ``The problem is that the difficulties always come first,
before the successes.''
   Rakowski has pledged to revitalize Poland's economy and
restructure its industry.
   Both Rakowski's government and the opposition, led by the
outlawed Solidarity free trade union, hope to use Mrs. Thatcher's
three-day visit to advance their arguments on the proper pace and
direction of political and economic reform in Poland.
   It appeared, however, that Mrs. Thatcher would tread a wary line.
The British official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Mrs.
Thatcher told the premier she had no desire to interfere in internal
Polish affairs.
   She arrived in a Royal Air Force jet and received a low-key
welcome from Rakowski at Warsaw's military airport.
   ``Hail, soldiers!'' Mrs. Thatcher said in Polish to a military
honor guard turned out to greet her.
   ``Hail, citizen premier,'' the honor guard replied, in unison,
also in Polish.
   Neither Mrs. Thatcher nor Rakowski, the Communist Party
propaganda chief who became premier Sept. 27, made public remarks at
the airport. They left immediately for a government guest house.
   State media have been calling attention to parallels between
Rakowski's goals and the success of Thatcherism in Britain _
including her tackling of trade unions and paring back of outdated,
state-subsidized industry.
   According to the British official, Rakowski said he was
determined to revive the economy although it was ``hard to have a
Marxist closing down Lenin.'' His reference was to Monday's
government order to shut the Lenin shipyard in Gdansk, birthplace of
the outlawed union Solidarity, for economic reasons Dec. 1.
   Solidarity founder Lech Walesa says the move is political, aimed
at punishing the yard for its support of Solidarity and depriving
the union of one of its most important bases.
   Walesa plans to greet Mrs. Thatcher on Friday when she becomes
the first Western head of government to travel to Gdansk to meet
him. Walesa made clear Wednesday his admiration of the Conservative
Party leader's hard-line approach to communism, but was less
enthusiastic about her domestic policies.
   ``I, Lech Walesa, and the whole of Polish society respect Mrs.
Margaret Thatcher, even love her,'' he told reporters in Gdansk.
``But the Mrs. Thatcher of foreign policy, not for the domestic
affairs of Britain.''
   On Wednesday evening, Mrs. Thatcher began her private schedule
with a one-hour call at the residence of Cardinal Jozef Glemp, the
Roman Catholic primate, followed by a meeting with six prominent
intellectuals that lasted more than an hour.
   The British official said she was warmly received by Glemp,
spiritual leader of the vast majority of Poland's 38 million people
who consider themselves Catholic.
   She told Glemp she wished ``to encourage those wanting to move
down the road to freedom,'' the official said, but noted again she
did not mean to interfere in Polish affairs.
   Aleksander Paszynski, one of intellectuals and a proponent of
private enterprise, said they stressed the ``unbreakable link
between economic and political reforms and the (government's) need
of gaining social support'' for any reform plan.
   ``It was a wonderful discussion, marvelous,'' Mrs. Thatcher told
reporters afterward.
   Her schedule Thursday includes meetings with Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski, the Polish leader, and a banquet at which she is
expected to make the major speech of her visit.
   She also is to visit the grave of a pro-Solidarity priest, the
Rev. Jerzy Popieluszko, slain in 1984 by security officers who were
later tried and imprisoned.
   On Friday, Mrs. Thatcher flies with Jaruzelski to Gdansk where
together they visit the Westerplatte penisula where German naval
forces opened fire on Sept. 1, 1939, in the opening shots of World
War II.
   Jaruzelski then returns to Warsaw while Mrs. Thatcher meets with
Walesa and other Solidarity leaders and visits the monument to slain
shipyard workers erected just outside the Lenin shipyard.
   Another meeting with Jaruzelski and a news conference closes out
the first visit by a British prime minister to Poland.
   Polish officials have been very eager for the visit and Warsaw
was festooned with Polish flags flying alongside the Union Jack in
greeting. Most newspapers carried her photo and a brief biography on
front pages.
   Officials want to convince Mrs. Thatcher of their seriousness in
reforming the economy, hoping that she will use her influence to
open up Western credits that were virtually closed off when martial
law was imposed in December in 1981.
   In addition to outdated industries, Poland has the East bloc's
largest foreign debt, approaching $40 billion, and would like new
financing to ease the debt burden.
</TEXT>
