<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 2136EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-StockScandal     11-02 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Stock Scandal,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigating Committee Will Call 3 Witnesses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigating committee decided Wednesday to call
the finance minister's former top aide and two other witnesses to
testify about an insider-trading stock scandal involving senior
politicians.
   The special parliamentary committee said it would call Tsuneo
Hattori, former secretary to Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, and
business associates Yasufumi Kawai and Shigeo Sugawara.
   They will be asked about their roles in buying stock of the real
estate firm Recruit-Cosmos Co., in Miyazawa's name, before it was
put on public sale. No date for their appearance was set.
   Opposition parties accuse Hiromasa Ezoe, founder of the parent
Recruit Inc., of making advance shares of Recruit-Cosmos available
to politicians, business leaders and journalists in return for
privileges or favors.
   When Recruit-Cosmos was listed on the over-the-counter market in
October 1986, the stock's value soared and those who had bought it
in advance made huge profits.
   A 13th politician became associated with the scandal Wednesday
when Katsuya Ikeda admitted that his brother bought advance shares
of Recruit-Cosmos. Ikeda, deputy secretary-general of the opposition
Komeito (Clean Government) Party, said in a televised news
conference he had no knowledge of the purchase.
   Finance Minister Miyazawa told the investigating committee last
week the sale of 10,000 Recruit-Cosmos shares in 1986 yielded a
profit of 22.7 million yen (then about $140,000), but said he did
not know the transaction was made in his name.
   He said Kawai, a business acquaintance of his former secretary
Hattori, asked the aide to let Miyazawa's name be used in the
purchase of Recruit-Cosmos shares from Sugawara, chairman of Do Best
Inc.
   Japanese media have said Do Best, a cosmetics importer, was the
middleman in the advance sale. The newspaper Asahi reported
Wednesday that Sugawara and Ezoe of Recruit Inc. were university
classmates in the early 1960s and Ezoe helped Sugawara set up his
company in 1974.
   The government has said the transactions were not illegal, but
the case raises ethical questions about the intimate links between
business and politics in Japan. Parliament tightened insider-trading
laws after the scandal broke last summer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
