<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0672 11-02 0843</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0672,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Seeks to Refine Abortion Stand</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS four grafs after 17th pvs, Pressed to..., to show
further questioning on abortion issue.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle, an ardent opponent of
abortion, said Wednesday he has no quarrel with a medical procedure
that he said is aimed at preventing conception after rape.
   The Republican vice presidential nominee said he would not
``construe that as being an abortion.''
   Quayle refused to acknowledge that the post-rape medical
procedure known as dilation and curettage, or D-and-C _ would amount
to abortion in the event that conception had occurred.
   ``Well, my position is that I understand from a medical situation
that, immediately after rape, that is reported, that a woman
normally, in fact, can go to the hospital and have a D-and-C at that
time, that is before the actual forming of a life,'' he said when
faced with the theoretical question of whether rape victims should
be allowed to have abortions.
   Quayle has repeatedly said in the past that he would accept
abortion only if it were necessary to save the life of the mother _
and he reiterated that position during a news conference here.
   But when asked pointedly whether he would expect a rape victim to
have the rapist's baby, he said, ``Hopefully they would seek medical
attention immediately, and under normal medical procedure, life and
conception would not even begin.''
   Quayle said that while his personal preference is that there
should be no abortion except to save a mother's life, a woman may
legally have the pregnancy terminated.
   Leonard Dinger, a spokesman for the National Right-to-Life
Committee in Washington, said, ``Our position is that there are
certain medical procedures that can prevent conception within 24
hours of that (rape) taking place.''
   ``If conception had already taken place, we would oppose it,'' he
said.
   Dr. Robert Shesser, a specialist in emergency care medicine at
George Washington University Medical Center in Washington, said in a
telephone interview that D-and-C is not the medical treatment most
immediately used for rape victims.
   Once it has been determined that conception has taken place, he
said in an interview, the victim is offered a so-called ``morning
after'' pill aimed at changing her body chemistry in a way to make
the uterus unreceptive to the growth of a fertilized egg.
   ``D-and-C is not an immediate post-rape procedure,'' Shesser
said, adding that emergency room physicians seldom resort to that
procedure, which is a scraping of the uterine lining.
   Quayle said Tuesday he favors having the Supreme Court overturn
the landmark Roe vs. Wade decision legalizing abortion, and said it
should be revert to a ``state's rights'' issue.
   On Wednesday, he was asked, theoretically whether a woman
impregnated through rape should be expected to bring the fetus to
full term.
   ``No, I understand that the medical procedure, a normal D-and-C,
right after rape, that you would not even get into a conception and
life would not even be formed,'' he said. ``That's my understanding
from a medical point of view, and therefore you wouldn't even get
into life being ... .''
   When asked how he would view a D-and-C if conception had taken
place, Quayle said, ``Doing it under this particular type of
situation, it's a normal medical procedure and I do not construe
that as being an abortion.''
   Pressed to explain his position further, he said, ``I think that
reporting of the rape, going into the hospital and, right after
that, having a D-and-C, I think is a perfectly normal response and
one that I would not put in the category of abortion.''
   As he headed toward his plane on leaving Memphis, Quayle was
asked again about his statements and told inquiring reporters, ``I
think it really is nit-picking (to question his abortion stand)
because of the votes that we have had'' against abortion.
   ``You're getting all sorts of very difficult medical
terminologies,'' he said. ``And you know what my position on
abortion is.''
   ``You're getting into all sorts of difficult sensitive areas that
I don't have all the answers to,'' the senator said.
   Quayle also said that ``I don't perceive'' that having the E and
C procedure right after a rape ``as being tantamount to abortion.''
   Quayle began his campaign day by fielding questions from local
reporters, at which time the abortion issue surfaced, and making
appearances at a high school rally and senior citizen's center. He
was traveling to Owensboro, Ky. later in the day.
   Questions about abortion have hounded Quayle in recent days,
particularly following his suggestion to a 12-year-old girl that she
should go ahead and give birth in a theoretical situation in which
she was raped by her father and became pregnant.
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis, campaigning in
California earlier this week, jumped on Quayle's statement, given
during an interview with a ``Children's Express'' reporter.
   Dukakis said such statements proved that the Republican Party has
``been on the wrong side of every issue of importance to women.''
</TEXT>
