<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 2141EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CheapShanties     11-02 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cheap Shanties,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Buys 1930s Shotgun Shanties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A charity group has bought 19 shotgun shacks
for $1 or $2 each and plans to turn the shanties into emergency
shelters for the rural poor.
   Madison Countians Allied Against Poverty won on bids submitted
Tuesday to the Board of Alderman on 19 of 20 homes. The buildings
made up a shantytown on the edge of Canton, which is 20 miles north
of Jackson.
   Sister Mary McGuire, executive director of the group, said the
renovated houses will be used to help people like one Madison County
family currently living in a house ``where you almost fall through
the floor when you walk in.''
   ``We're interested in helping a couple of burned-out families and
we're interested in using them for several families out in the
country that live in housing that is in a dilapidated condition,''
she said.
   She also said the shacks could be used ``as a room added on to an
existing house.''
   The shanties were built in the 1930s to house lumberyard workers.
The one- and two-room, tin roof buildings lack electricity and
indoor plumbing.
   City officials bought the property in September and wanted to
tear down the dilapidated structures and offer the site for
development.
   But the state Department of Archives and History, saying the
structures had historical architectural significance, asked city
officials to take bids on the houses instead.
   MadCAAP won the first 19 bids, but Moses Wright of Canton bid
$500 on the 20th shack and assumed ownership of the building. He did
not indicate how he intended to use it.
   The charity group is making plans to move the rundown shacks, and
estimates it will cost about $800 to $1,000 each. Sister McGuire
said volunteers will help with the renovations.
   The organization's bids were welcomed by Mayor Sidney Runnels,
who had expressed hope the group would get some of the houses.
   ``I think it's a good cause,'' Runnels said. ``We're very
supportive of what they are doing.''
   The homes can't be used as residences within the city because
they don't meet the city code.
   Only three families still live in the shantytown, and they are
expected to be relocated by the end of this month. The city, using
money from a block grant, has been relocating residents of the
shantytown since August.
</TEXT>
