<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Palestinians 1stLd-Writethru a0621 11-02 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Palestinians, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0621,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Predict Greater Rebellion; Soldiers Kill 1, Wound 20</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to UPDATE with more wounded in new violence and
INSERTS 2 grafs after 13th pvs, Eighteen Palestinians ... with
details. PICKS up 14th pvs, Among hard-line ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians said the strong showing of
right-wing parties in Israel's elections would feed the 11-month-old
rebellion in the occupied lands, where soldiers killed one Arab on
Wednesday and wounded at least 29.
   Said Kenaan, a businessman in Nablus, said the Israeli electorate
had rejected peace efforts and was determined to keep all the West
Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in
the 1967 war.
   ``It's obvious Israelis don't want peace, but we will hit back,''
he declared. ``The moderate voice in the Palestinian camp is
finished.''
   Kenaan supports the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Hanna Siniora, editor of the pro-PLO daily Al Fajr, said giving
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's Likud bloc and its right-wing allies
the chance of forming a government meant voting for ``more tension
and confrontation.''
   ``The Palestinians will now only intensify their efforts to end
the occupation and achieve national rights,'' he said.
   Wednesday's death brought to at least 306 the number of
Palestinians killed since the uprising began Dec. 8. Ten Israelis
also have been slain.
   Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza closed their shops and
halted transportation Wednesday, the anniversary of the Balfour
declaration of Nov. 2, 1917, in which Britain recognized the Zionist
movement's goal of a Jewish state in Palestine. They also held a
general strike Tuesday, election day.
   Several violent incidents were reported in the occupied
territories.
   Army spokesmen said soldiers shot and killed a 20-year-old
Palestinian who confronted them when they chased masked Palestinian
youths into his home at Qalqiliya, a West Bank town.
   Arab witnesses identified the victim as Jalal Fayoumi and said
his 45-year-old mother, Mahdieh, suffered a gunshot wound. The army
spokesman's office confirmed the wounding.
   Officials at Arab hospitals said an 18-year-old youth was wounded
in the stomach during the confrontation at Qalqiliya.
   Eighteen Palestinians were wounded in other incidents, two of
them seriously in the chest and stomach, hospital officials said.
The army said it was checking the casualty reports.
   The army command said a soldier was hit and injured by a building
block in Nablus and that troops shot and wounded nine Palestinians
in disturbances in the Gaza Strip.
   In the Arab quarter of Jabl Mukabar in Arab east Jerusalem,
border police fired after a Palestinian tried to seize a policeman's
gun, police spokesman Rafi Levy said. He said police later arrested
eight Palestinians.
   Among hard-line parties winning places in the Knesset, the
120-member Israeli parliament, was one that advocates expelling the
1.5 million Palestinians of the West Bank and Gaza to Arab
countries. Its name, Moledet, means Homeland in Hebrew.
   Shamir has vowed never to return any of the land Israel captured
in 1967, but Foreign Minister Shimon Peres and his rival Labor Party
favor trading some of it for peace. Labor and Likud have been in a
tenuous ``national unity'' coalition since the indecisive 1984
election.
   Siniora said most Palestinians greeted the election result with
gloom, but felt a right-wing government at least would ``finally
make decision-making possible. The decision will either be for peace
or for carrying out the right-wing platform of non-withdrawal, which
will lead to confrontation with the Palestinians and the Arab
countries.''
   Asaad Saftawi, 55, a PLO supporter from the Gaza Strip, said, ``A
Likud-led government will destroy a golden opportunity for peace.''
</TEXT>
