<HEAD>Court Sentences Palestinian Hijacker To 25 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALLETTA, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court sentenced a Palestinian to the
maximum 25 years in prison Wednesday after he admitted killing two
women passengers during a 1985 hijacking penalty.
   Judge Wallace Gunia pronounced sentence on Omar Mohammed Ali
Rezaq, 25, after a two-day trial. Rezak pleaded guilty Tuesday to
seven charges.
   The Lebanese-born Rezaq was the lone survivor of three
Palestinian gunmen who seized an Egyptair Boeing 737 flying from
Athens to Cairo on Nov. 23, 1985.
   He stood motionless and made no comment when the judge pronounced
sentence.
   Rezak pleaded guilty to killing Scarlet Maria Rogenkamp, of
Oceanside, Calif., and Nitzan Mendelson, an Israeli woman, after
denying the charges in pre-trial testimony.
   The two women were forced to go to the doorway of the plane after
Jewish and American passengers were singled out. The two were shot
and thrown from the plane to the tarmac.
   Rezaq had told the court he belonged to the Egyptian
Revolutionary Organization. He said it was made up of people from
Lebanon, Tunisia and Egypt, but gave no details.
   Rezaq also admitted to the attempted killing of four other
people: two Americans, Patrick Scott Baker of White Salmon, Wash.,
and Jackie Pflug of Pasadena, Texas; and two Israelis.
   he said the hijacking was a protest against Egypt's political
system, which he claimed was ``destroying the future of the
Palestinians.''
   Sixty people died in the hijacking and the storming of the plane
by Egyptian soldiers.
</TEXT>
