<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Venezuela     11-02 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Venezuela,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least 25 Students, Several Police Hurt in Riots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CAPLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Student riots spread across Venezuela
Wednesday over the killing of 14 fishermen by Venezuelan troops,
injuring at least 25 students and several police, said student
groups and journalists on the scene.
   Pitched battles took place between students and police and
National Guard units, they said. Clashes were reported at Caracas,
Merida, Maracaibo and Valencia.
   The riots followed violent protests Tuesday in which 12 students
from Caracas' Central University were injured.
   Government officials have called the shooting of the fishermen
last Saturday at the Venezuelan-Colombian border a ``lamentable
confusion.'' Two survivors swore in military court Tuesday they were
simple Venezuelan fishermen and not Colombian leftist guerrillas as
the military originally claimed.
   In the Andes mountains capital of Merida, about 300 miles
southwest of Caracas, students rioted down the main avenue, burning
four cars, sacking stores and breaking the front windows of seven
banks, according to Ramon Diaz Suarez, a reporter for Frontera
newspaper.
   He said 10 students were wounded by shotgun blasts in daylong
battles with police and National Guard units.
   Merida is the site of several universities and home to thousands
of students from across the country.
   Merida state Gov. Orlando Guttierez held emergency meetings with
military authorities to ``determine the necessary steps,'' said Diaz
Suarez.
   Three students in Caracas were wounded in street battles with
police, said a student representative contacted on the campus of
Central University.
   Bernardo Ansidey, president of the student group, said the
students were hit by shotgun blasts Wednesday before they could
retreat to university grounds.
   By law, police are barred from entering the campus and can fire
on the students only if they come out onto the avenues surrounding
the university.
   Ansidey said demonstrations would continue to protest the
shooting of the fishermen near El Amparo, about 365 miles southwest
of Caracas.
   He said students also were demanding the release of Jose Tomas
Pinto, an education student jailed by authorities for ``military
rebellion'' and now on a hunger strike in a Caracas jail.
   Students in universities at Maracaibo, the oil city about 350
miles west of Caracas, and Valencia, about 60 miles west of Caracas,
also burned vehicles and fought with police, reporters said.
   Police in Valencia were ordered to hold their fire and instead
fired tear gas, while students took soda bottles off a delivery
truck and lobbed them at the police, said Maria Luisa Gotto,
reporter for El Carabobeno.
   She said fighting went on nine hours without showing signs of of
letting up, adding that several police were taken to a hospital with
wounds from rocks and bottles.
   Police had no immediate comment on the riots.
</TEXT>
