<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 2155EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FlagTrial     11-02 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Flag Trial,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Individual Trials for Blacks Protesting Confederate
Flag</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILLIP RAWLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Wednesday ordered individual
trials for 14 black legislators charged with trespassing during an
attempt to remove the Confederate battle flag from the state Capitol.
   Montgomery County District Judge Craig Miller made the decision
in response to a request by the prosecution.
   Prosecutors presented 2{ hours of testimony against the first
defendant, State Rep. Thomas Reed, and Miller rejected a defense
request to throw out the case.
   Then he indefinitely recessed the non-jury case, citing his
crowded docket and scheduling conflicts affecting witnesses and the
prominent civil rights lawyers who have traveled to Montgomery
without pay to represent Reed.
   Ernestine Sapp of Tuskegee, a defense attorney, predicted Reed's
trial might resume ``after the first of the year.'' She said the
indefinite delay ``gives time to settle the case'' by dismissing the
charges.
   Assistant District Attorney David Glanzer said he remained ready
to proceed at any time.
   The legislators were charged with criminal trespassing for
grabbing a fence around the Capitol, which is closed for renovation,
on Feb. 2 during a demonstration decrying the Confederate flag as a
symbol of racism. The charge carries a penalty of up to three months
in jail and a $500 fine.
   During opening arguments, Glanzer said police repeatedly warned
the legislators they would be arrested if they touched the fence,
and that putting one's fingers through a fence constitutes
trespassing under Alabama law.
   The defense argued that no crime occurred because the legislators
never entered the Capitol grounds.
   ``Now we go to the ridiculous _ whether someone's fingers went
through the fence. That's ridiculous even for Alabama,'' defense
attorney J.L. Chestnut of Selma said.
   Reed, 60, the senior black in the Alabama Legislature, went on
trial first because ``Tom was nominally in charge'' of the protest
and was arrested first, Chestnut said.
   Reed was convicted Sept. 30 on federal extortion charges, and a
court has ordered his removal from office upon his sentencing. He
claims the extortion case was built against him because of his
threat to physically pull down the Confederate flag from atop the
Capitol if the Republican governor failed to do it before the
opening day of the 1988 legislative session.
   Gov. Guy Hunt says he views the flag as a historic emblem and
refuses to remove it unless the Legislature votes to do so. A
resolution to remove the flag failed to win passage in the House on
Feb. 2.
   State Capitol Police Chief Cecil Humphrey testified that two or
three days before the demonstration, Hunt's legal adviser, Mark
Montiel, made the decision to charge Reed and other black
legislators with trespassing if they tried to enter the fenced
Capitol grounds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
