<HEAD>Worst Storm Blackout in 20 Years, Road Deaths Caused</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unseasonal snow storm caused central
Sweden's worst power blackout in 20 years Wednesday, the national
news agency TT said.
   At least three persons were killed in accidents on icy roads.
   The power outage affected more than 50,000 households in a wide
area north and west of Stockholm, TT said. Some homes were without
power 20 hours later.
   Trains from north Sweden were delayed up to 10 hours after the
storm's winds of up to 90 mph knocked trees across power lines and
railroad tracks, Swedish television reported.
   An Italian truck driver lost control of his vehicle and caused a
pileup of four passenger cars and three longhaul trucks on a major
highway in Ostergotland province, newspaper reports said Wednesday.
The driver suffered a slight injury but no one else was reported
hurt.
