<2ND_LINE>AM-Rish Trial,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Woman Guilty in Businessman's Abduction, Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANKAKEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman accused of helping to lure a
businessman from his home and burying him alive in a botched ransom
attempt was found guilty Wednesday on murder and kidnapping charges.
   Nancy Rish, 26, was convicted in the death of businessman Stephen
Small after a Winnebago County jury deliberated for an hour and 40
minutes.
   ``This jury's verdict was swift and just,'' said prosecutor
Michael Ficaro. Small, 40, member of a prominent media family and
great-grandson of the late Illinois Gov. Len Small, was lured from
his home by kidnapers who placed him in a homemade box and buried it
in sandy soil on Sept. 2, 1987.
   Telephone calls were made to Small's wife, Nancy, seeking a
ransom, but she was unable to decipher instructions for a drop-off
and no ransom was ever offered. Small suffocated when a makeshift
air supply system failed.
   Ms. Rish's live-in boyfriend Daniel Edwards was convicted of
Small's murder and kidnapping in May and sentenced to death.
Prosecutors said they would not seek the death penalty for Ms. Rish.
   Kankakee County Circuit Judge John Michela set her sentencing for
Dec. 6.
   The jury, which was sequestered, was selected in Rockford because
of extensive publicity in the Kankakee area.
   Ficaro had argued that Ms. Rish and Edwards believed the
abduction would lead to a $1 million ransom and ``that ticket to
easy street ... life in the fast lane.''
   He called Ms. Rish a ``gold digger'' who lured Small from his
home so Edwards could bury him alive as part of a plot to collect
the ransom.
   Ms. Rish's attorneys maintained that she was the victim of
mistaken identity and that Edwards had been with another blond
person when the crimes were committed.
   Ms. Rish took the stand on her own behalf near the end of the
trial, acknowledging she took Edwards to various sites significant
to the crimes but saying she did not know what Edwards was doing.
</TEXT>
