<1ST_LINE>r a AM-INS-Indictment     11-02 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-INS-Indictment,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Atlanta INS Chief Charged In Illegal Aliens Conspiracy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former director of the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service office in Atlanta and a South Carolina lawyer
were charged in an indictment unsealed Wednesday with using false
information to allow aliens to remain in the United States illegally.
   The federal indictment charges Louis Richard, the former INS
chief, and attorney James Dunbar of Columbia, S.C., with one count
of conspiracy and 22 counts of making false representations to the
INS to obtain benefits for aliens.
   Richard and Dunbar pleaded innocent at an arraignment Wednesday
in Atlanta federal court. Richard was released on a $10,000 bond and
Dunbar on a $20,000 bond, said U.S. Attorney Robert L. Barr Jr.
   A person answering the telephone at Richard's Doraville home said
Richard would not comment. Repeated calls were made to Dunbar's home
Wednesday night, but his telephone was busy.
   ``The offenses basically relate to efforts by aliens to be
admitted to the country or to remain here in the country, under
certain exceptions in INS regulations,'' Barr said. ``Were it not
for the false representations brought by Dunbar, they would not
remain in the United States.''
   Barr said the indictment charges that Dunbar would bring the
false information to Richard, who would in turn approve the benefits
for the aliens even though he knew the information wasn't true.
   Richard was transferred from Atlanta to Washington during the
investigation and retired four months ago, Barr said.
   The prosecutor said both Dunbar and Richard each face up to 115
years in prison and $3.65 million in fines if convicted on all
charges.
</TEXT>
