<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brown-Rapes     11-02 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brown-Rapes,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brown University Women Protest Recent Rapes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIMBERLY M. SHEARIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 Brown University students, some
hugging friends who sobbed, gathered Wednesday to protest two recent
rapes near campus and tell their own horror stories of sexual
violence.
   Police said both rape victims were attacked near the Ivy League
campus within two weeks of each other last month. The assaults
spurred appeals to female students to take the campus shuttle or
walk in groups.
   Providence police and Brown security officials say they believe
the same man may have been invovled in both rapes, since both women
were attacked at knifepoint as they were walking alone at night.
   They have declined to elaborate on the similarities and will only
say their investigation is continuing.
   Police have passed around flyers warning women of the attacks and
giving them tips on how to protect themselves.
   About 25 people spoke at the demonstration, including some who
talked about being raped by family members, brothers of friends,
friends of the family and others.
   Most speakers criticized what they described as a society of men
who think when a woman smiles at them, she wants sex, and family
members who blame women for incest and date rapes.
   They said they were also tired of not being able to walk where
they want and wear what they want.
   ``I'm not going to say I can't ... because that's like having
something stripped away from me,'' said Beth Bird, a senior, who
said she wants women students to form a ``counter-terrorist'' group
to fight back against men who try to assault them.
   Kathy Hathaway, a Brown senior and organizer of the speak-out,
said she and some classmates taking the campus shuttle at night are
angry their freedom is restricted.
   ``I resent the fact of feeling powerless,'' she said. ``When I
walk out of the library at night, there's a dilemma. It's not an
automatic decision to take the shuttle.''
   Hathaway said the speak-out was held to allow people to air their
feelings.
   ``On campus and in the Providence community as a whole, there's
been so much emotion ... but no forum to release the emotion,''
Hathaway said. ``We wanted to provide that arena.''
   The speak-out was to be followed by a 30-minute ``Take Back the
Night'' all-women march near the scene of the two rapes and a
candlelight vigil on the campus green. Men would be allowed to
participate in the vigil, she said.
</TEXT>
