<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Sex     11-02 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Sex,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey Says Attitudes Toward Sex More Conservative</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More Britons condemn homosexuality and favor
stricter morals, possibly in reaction to the spread of AIDS, an
independent research group said Thursday.
   The findings were part of a survey of 2,847 Britons conducted in
1987 by the independent Social and Community Planning Research
group, which has published reports on social attitudes annually
since 1983.
   ``Although we cannot be absolutely sure, it seems certain that
there is a link between stricter morals and concern over the spread
of AIDS,'' said Sharon Witherspoon, a senior researcher and joint
editor of the report.
   ``Our analysis shows that the type of person who tends to be less
sympathetic and more censorious toward AIDS sufferers is exactly the
same person who will be less liberal in their views on general
matters of sexual morality.''.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer. It is most often spread through sexual
contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood
or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring. AIDS
is fatal, with no known cure.
   The British survey found 74 percent of those polled thought
homosexual relations were always or generally wrong, 12 percent more
than in 1983.
   The number of those surveyed who thought sex before marriage was
wrong rose from 23 percent in 1985 to 25 percent in 1987. Those who
disapproved of extramarital affairs rose from 83 percent in 1983 to
88 percent last year.
   Reseachers found ambivalent attitudes on AIDS. Although 57
percent of respondents felt that ``most people with AIDS have only
themselves to blame,'' about 60 percent believed that ``people who
have AIDS get much less sympathy from society than they ought to
get.''
   One-third of the respondents agreed more money should be spent on
research into a cure for AIDS, but less than 10 percent thought more
should be spent on care for AIDS victims.
   That finding indicated ``a somewhat chilling lack of strong
concern for increasing the resources available for helping
sufferers,'' said Lindsay Brook, a senior researcher and co-editor
of the book.
   The survey found that 60 percent of those polled believed
teen-agers under 16 should not be given contraceptives, 10 percent
more than in 1983.
   The authors said the survey was carried out on a random sample of
people living in all areas of Britain except Northern Ireland.
Interviews were conducted at respondents' homes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
