<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday Nov. 3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>With a Little Luck, Big Takeovers Can Boost Small Portfolios</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tiny investment club in the Midwest _
appropriately named ``ESP'' _ expects to see its stock portfolio
expand by about 13 percent as a result of Philip Morris Cos.'
mammoth $13 billion takeover of Kraft Inc.
   The group, which consists mostly of retired couples from
Columbus, Ohio, bought a block of Kraft stock three years ago for
around $36 a share, when the company was still known as Dart &
Kraft, explained member LaVonne Raney.
   But contrary to what its name might imply, none of ESP's members
could have sensed Philip Morris would be snapping up those shares
now for $106 apiece in cash, giving the club about $7,000 in
``winnings,'' as Mrs. Raney puts it.
   ``It's a little bit like the lottery ... if you want to be
cynical about the whole thing. A few lucky people are winning, the
rest aren't,'' said Larry Biehl, co-founder and director of Bailard
Biehl & Kaiser, a San Mateo, Calif., investment advisory firm.
   Biehl and many others in his field say that while their clients
are envious of the potential windfall awaitikcPqt
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ckholders of Kraft</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   and other recent giant takeover targets, such as RJR Nabisco Inc. or
Pillsbury Inc., there's no big rush to play Wall Street's takeover
game.
   They term most individual investors in America as long-term
planners, who might be saving for retirement or their childrens'
college education. That's opposed to those who might dash off to
their discount brokers minutes after reading of a takeover battle or
getting a ``tip.''
   ``The planning client is an entirely different animal than the
transaction-oriented client,'' explained Hank Madden, a financial
planner in IDS Financial Services Inc.'s Jacksonville, Fla., office.
   ``The planning client strategically moves. They do not get caught
up in the turmoil of the daily tactical moves of the market.
Transactionary (clients) will deal with a reactionary perspective.''
   Tim Lucum, a retired Seattle pharmacist who belongs to an
investment club similar to ESP, puts himself mainly in the first
category. He says his group, which calls itself the Deadenders,
won't be trying to guess where the next big takeover will take
place, but rather looks for what it considers to be undervalued or
recession-proof stock.
   ``We have a stock selection guide,'' Lucum explained. ``We are
looking at what the company has done in the past 10 years. If we
think a stock will double in about five years, we'll buy it.''
   Lucum said his club made a special exception in buying Gillette
Co. stock, when the personal care giant was involved in a battle
over control of its board of directors. The proxy fight pressured
the stock higher, but even so, Lucum thought the shares were a good,
long-term value.
   Jay Goldinger, who runs the Beverly Hills, Calif., investment
firm Capital Insight Inc., says the latest takeover craze _ which
includes a $20 billion bid for RJR Nabisco from Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts & Co. and a $5.23 billion bid for Pillsbury from Grand
Metropolitan PLC _ may not be affecting individual investors so much
because many have bought into stock or bond mutual funds.
   ``The individual goes into a mutual fund these days and doesn't
tend to react. It's mostly institutional investors that are
involved,'' he said.
   Madden agreed, adding, ``I think the average investor is very
ill-informed. They look at what's happening with Kraft and say how
is that going to affect me. `I'm not going to get a discount on
cheese.'''
   On the other hand, institutional investors, which include many
large pension funds and insurance companies, are far more
sophisticated and tend to buy and sell large blocks of stock.
   Still, Biehl says the takeover frenzy is reviving excitement in
the stock market after several months in the doldrums.
   ``It puts the market back on the front page,'' he said. ``People
were looking at the market after the Oct. 19 (1987) crash as being
something like boxing. They suspect it's fixed.
   ``What we're seeing lately is some heavyweight matches.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday Nov. 3</NOTE>
