<1ST_LINE>a p PM-Congress-Glance ADV07   11-02 0914</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Glance, ADV 07,0934</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, Nov. 7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Congressional Races At a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief look at some of the hottest Senate and House
races on the Nov. 8 ballot:
   
   SENATE
   
   CONNECTICUT _ Sen. Lowell Weicker, the Senate's most liberal
Republican, had his hands full trying to maintain his perennial
political balancing act against a challenge from Democratic state
Attorney General Joseph Lieberman. Polls show the two in a dead
heat. Lieberman was scoring well with appeals to environmental and
``family'' issues, and charges that Weicker ignores the state to
fight Quixotic civil liberties battles.
   FLORIDA _ Late polls showed Democratic Rep. Buddy MacKay held a
narrow edge over his GOP opponent, Rep. Connie Mack, in their battle
over the seat of retiring Democrat Lawton Chiles. MacKay, a folksy
campaigner, has traveled the state with a populist message and harsh
criticism for his rival for votes against federal environmental,
child nutrition and elderly care programs. Mack has sought to
portray MacKay as a liberal outside the state's mainstream.
   MINNESOTA _ In a race dominated by negative advertising, GOP Sen.
David Durenberger, once viewed as vulnerable, maintained a lead in
the polls going into the final week against Democratic challenger
Hubert H. Humphrey III, the state attorney general. Durenberger
seemed to live down problems that included marital difficulties and
disclosure of national security secrets to a Jewish group. Humphrey,
a lackluster campaigner, suffered by comparison to his father, the
late vice president.
   MISSISSIPPI _ One of the GOP's best hopes for picking off a
Democratic Senate seat and recouping on 1986 losses in the South
lies in Rep. Trent Lott, the party's No. 2 leadership official in
the House. His well-organized and amply-funded campaign had pulled
to an eight-point lead over three-term Democratic Rep. Wayne Dowdy
by mid October, but was bothered by news reports about benefits for
the state for which Lott claimed credit, but was shown to have
previously opposed. Dowdy hoped to combine overwhelming black
support with votes from rural whites for a come-from-behind win.
   NEBRASKA _ Former Democratic Gov. Robert Kerrey is the clear
favorite to knock off incumbent Republican Sen. David Karnes, who
was appointed to his Senate seat to fill a vacancy in 1987. Karnes
rebounded from large poll deficits after winning a bruising GOP
primary, but lost momentum after commenting ``we need fewer
farmers'' during a debate.
   NEVADA _ This up-and-down race promises a close finish. Incumbent
Republican Sen. Chic Hecht, whose fumbling style made him the most
vulnerable incumbent, has fought back hard and closed the gap with
Democratic Gov. Richard Bryan. Hecht has been hurt by his failure to
head off using Nevada as the site for a nuclear waste repository;
Bryan ran into criticism over purchase of an expensive executive jet
for the state.
   NEW JERSEY _ The most slashing negative attacks in any major race
this year have accompanied the battle between incumbent Democrat
Frank Lautenberg and GOP challenger Pete Dawkins. Dawkins, a Rhodes
scholar, former football star and Army general, has called his
opponent a scheming profiteer; Lautenberg, a self-made millionaire
businessman, has tagged Dawkins a carpetbagger and a liar.
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Mike Lowry, an unabashed liberal Democrat, is
battling conservative former Sen. Slade Gorton, for the seat of
retiring GOP Sen. Daniel Evans. The race hinged largely on images _
Lowry trying to tone down his scruffy, arm-waving persona and Gorton
apologizing for the aloofness that contributed to his 1986
re-election defeat.
   WISCONSIN _ A late spurt by state Senate Republican leader Susan
Engeleiter appeared to be falling short of catching Democratic
millionaire businessman Herbert Kohl, a political novice who bought
his way into public prominence with millions of dollars in TV
advertising. They are seeking the seat of retiring Democrat William
Proxmire.
   
   HOUSE
   
   CALIFORNIA 19TH: Rep. Robert Lagomarsino, a seven-term
Republican, faces a spirited challenge from Democratic state Sen.
Gary K. Hart in what seems to be the most expensive House race in
the country, with both candidates expected to spend about $1.2
million. Lagomarsino is a strong supporter of the Nicaraguan Contra
rebels and Star Wars, both of which Hart opposes. It's the district
Ronald Reagan will go home to in January, and the Democrats want
Hart to represent him in the House when he does.
   SOUTH CAROLINA 4TH: Freshman Rep. Liz Patterson is one of the
most endangered Democrats in the House, and Republican attorney Knox
White is trying hard to recapture a district that usually votes
strongly for the GOP.
   NEBRASKA 2ND: This open seat was vacated when GOP Rep. Hal Daub
made an unsuccessful run for the Senate nomination. It's developed
into a costly fight between former Democratic state Sen. Peter
Hoagland and Republican Jerry Schenken, a pathologist.
   NEW JERSEY 3RD: State Sen. Frank Pallone hopes to keep this
Jersey Shore district for the Democrats, who held it for 24 years
under Rep. James Howard until his death last spring. Pallone faces
supermarket chain owner Joseph Azzolina, a former state legislator
who was enlisted for the race prior to Howard's death.
   RHODE ISLAND 1ST: House Banking Committee Chairman Fernand St
Germainm, seeking a 15th term, was dubbed the most vulnerable
Democratic incumbent by the National Republican Congressional
Committee and faced renewed reports of an investigation of alleged
ethical misconduct. Late polls showed him running even with GOP
challenger Ronald K. Machtley.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, Nov. 7</NOTE>
