<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 1330EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:Glover ADV09   11-02 0850</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Glover, ADV 09,0878</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Nov 9 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>An Actor Idealist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Danny Glover does not hesitate to call himself an
idealist: The actor hopes he can make the real world a better place
through the world of make-believe.
   ``I deal with fantasy,'' he said. ``I deal with the process that
in my mind things are going to change. I give that as a given. It
takes a concerted effort on all our parts to bring about that
change.''
   Glover has tried to do just that in different ways. He was a
student activist in the late 1960s when he attended San Francisco
State College, and his involvement with the anti-war movement
inspired him to pursue acting.
   ``I thought drama was a way of touching people, of providing them
with information, getting them to react.''
   In his latest film, ``Bat 21,'' Glover plays Birddog, a Vietnam
War spotter pilot who must rescue a middle-aged officer (Gene
Hackman), who is stranded in enemy territory. The movie centers on
their relationship, which develops without their ever setting eyes
on one another.
   The experience of not being able to see Hackman reminded Glover
of an exercise from his theatrical training.
   ``You're blindfolded and someone leads you around and talks to
you. They can be just having a converation with you and you can't
see where you're going, You're just listening to them and hearing
them. It heightens your other senses in doing this, establishing a
relationship wuith just trust in listening and hearing.
   ``The key to acting is just listening.''
   Glover brought this approach to ``Bat 21.''
   ``I would sometimes read some of the lines to Gene and put myself
in the position where I couldn't see what he was doing,'' Glover
said. ``I used the intonations with his voice, used whatever he
brought to the situation to try to ascertain what was happening.''
   The rock star Stevie Wonder once made a group of critics listen
to his new record blindfolded so they could hear the music the way
he did: without the benefit of sight.
   ``A perfect example if you use Stevie,'' Glover said. ``He's able
to interpret who you are, what you're about, just by listening to
you. He'll say, `I saw Aretha Franklin.' His interpration of seeing
is hearing the words and being affected by the words.''
   Glover, the son of postal employees, grew up in San Francisco.
Through an actor's workshop in the mid-70s, he met South African
playwright Athol Fugard and appeared in four of his plays, notably
``Master Harold ... and the Boys.''
   His first major film role came in 1984 when he appeared as Sally
Field's farmhand, Moze, in ``Places of the Heart.'' He played a
heavy in ``Witness,'' and starred as a cop in ``Lethal Weapon.'' He
received an Academy Award nomination for his role of Mr. in ``The
Color Purple,'' the film version of Alice Walker's best-selling
novel.
   Although, ``Mr.,'' Whoopi Goldberg's abusive husband, was widely
regarded as evil and drew criticism for its negative portrayal of a
black male, Glover felt sympathy for the character.
   ``I try to instill in every character I'm involved with a sense
of completion, a sense of many facets. I don't think that `Mr.'
defined himself as being a bad person,'' he said.
   Glover sought to understand the origins of his character's anger.
   ``I said to myself that he wanted to feel good about himself,''
he said. ``He wanted to feel loved, he wanted to feel close to
someone. He was capable of loving and feeling close to his wife and
anything short of that made him feel different.
   ``If you think of something hard enough and in the process of
thinking about it, something diverts your attention, it makes you
upset.''
   In ``Bat 21'' as well, Glover worked hard to make his character a
complete person.
   ``I tried to focus on every part of him. I was dealing with a man
who had a passion for flying ever since he was a kid. He certainly
felt that he had the short end of things. He had the knowledge and
ability of white pilots but was looked over.
   ``He had a strong sense of himself as a pilot and that maintained
him and allowed him to go on.''
   Glover's sense of himself comes from believing in the possibility
of change. In college, that belief came from the civil rights
movement.
   ``Watching people attacked, that had a profound impact on me.
When I came to college, I was open to the possibility of growing
politically. I came at a very unique time in history. All of us were
throwing away those shackles and confinement.''
   And after politics, Glover brought his idealism to the stage.
   ``It allowed me more contact with people,'' he said. ``I wasn't
distancing myself in a lot of economic theories. I did stuff that I
thought affected people. They laugh, they cry, they're moved by it.
Nothing does that more than art.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Nov. 9</NOTE>
