<1ST_LINE>a p BC-Candidates-SocialSecurity Adv00   11-02 0780</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Candidates-Social Security, Adv00,0805</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Upon Receipt</NOTE>
<HEAD>Social Security Turns Up As Political Hot Potato</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Social Security, in sickness and in health, has
been one of the Democratic Party's most potent political weapons of
the 1980s.
   Democrat Michael Dukakis hoped to galvanize elderly voters once
again with a broad-brush charge that Republican George Bush would
``raid the Social Security trust fund'' if elected.
   Bush sought to blunt the charge not only by vowing to keep his
hands off Social Security, but by accusing Dukakis of dipping into a
Massachusetts pension fund for $27 million to help balance his state
budget this year.
   Some lobbyists for the elderly are worried that regardless of
sworn statements and good intentions, Social Security will be a
tempting target next year and into the 1990s for politicians trying
to balance the federal budget.
   Robert Strauss, co-chairman of the National Economic Commission
which is supposed to recommend ways next spring to balance the
budget, touched off a firestorm in September by saying the only way
to cure the deficit is ``to go to Social Security, Medicare and
entitlements generally and ... defense.''
   Both the Dukakis and Bush campaigns disavowed the statement by
Strauss, a former Democratic Party chairman.
   Thirty-eight million retirees, disabled workers and their
families count on that check in the mail on the third day of each
month from Social Security. They will get a 4 percent increase this
January.
   The $210 billion retirement and disability program, on the verge
of bankruptcy five short years ago, now is piling up huge surpluses.
Its trust funds which grew to $69 billion last year, will add $40
billion more in 1988 and are expected to swell to $646 billion by
the end of 1995.
   Dukakis has claimed Bush will be forced to ``raid'' those trust
funds if he is serious about cutting the capital gains tax, spending
more on the Pentagon and balancing the budget.
   Bush has said repeatedly he will not touch Social Security.
   ``If elected your president, I pledge that no one will take your
Social Security away from you,'' Bush says in a political flyer
aimed at the elderly.
   Although Social Security's trust funds technically are listed
apart from the rest of the federal budget, they are lumped together
when the deficit is tallied.
   Federal law prohibits spending Social Security's reserves on
other programs, but every dollar added to the trust funds reduces
the overall deficit.
   And since the trust funds must be invested in interest-bearing
U.S. securities, they reduce the amount the government must borrow
in private markets. The government uses the funds generated by
selling bonds to Social Security to cover the operating deficit in
other programs.
   Social Security didn't save Jimmy Carter in 1980 or Walter
Mondale in 1984, but Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., said it was the issue
that cost Republicans control of the Senate in 1986.
   Bush says he deserves credit with President Reagan for the 1983
legislation that restored Social Security's fiscal health.
   But Dukakis and others say Bush shares the blame for the deep
cuts Reagan sought in Social Security after taking office in 1981.
   As president of the Senate, Bush cast a tie-breaking vote on May
9, 1985, for a budget freeze that would have blocked Social
Security's 1986 cost-of-living adjustment.
   That freeze never materialized. Reagan, after initially
supporting it, abandoned the package and it died. Afterwards, he
adopted the hands-off policy toward Social Security Bush promises to
emulate.
   Bush points out that Dukakis voted that same year at a National
Governors Association meeting in favor of a federal budget freeze.
Dukakis did that, but only after waging a losing effort to exempt
Social Security.
   Dukakis did divert a $27 million surplus from a state pension
fund this year, but he says it was only after fully paying this
year's obligation, and he takes credit for a 1987 reform law that
marks the first time the state has ever set money aside for future
pension obligations.
   Bush's two top economic advisers, Martin Feldstein and Michael
Boskin, have been prominent academic critics of Social Security.
   Feldstein has argued that Social Security depresses private
savings. He also has proposed restricting cost-of-living increases
to the Consumer Price Index minus 2 percentage points.
   Boskin, in a 1986 book, ``Too Many Promises: The Uncertain Future
of Social Security,'' proposed to revamp Social Security to separate
its insurance and welfare aspects.
   But some Democratic economists, looking for ways to reduce the
deficit, are talking quietly of making more retirees pay income tax
on Social Security benefits. Only one retiree in 10 now is taxed on
Social Security.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881102-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 2339EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a p BC-Candidates-Deficit ADV00   11-02 1604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Candidates-Deficit, ADV 00,1644</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bush Plans `Flexible Freeze'; Dukakis Would Target Tax Cheats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Ronald Reagan entered the White House in
1981, the national debt was under $1 trillion. Today it has soared
to $2.6 trillion. Just paying the interest on that mountain of debt
now costs American taxpayers more than $150 billion a year.
   So what do Vice President George Bush and Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis propose to do about the deficit?
   Despite the Republican's talk of a ``flexible freeze'' on most
government spending and the Democrat's hopes of reaping tens of
billions of dollars through tougher tax enforcement, economists say
neither presidential candidate has put forward a credible plan for
mopping up the tidal wave of red ink.
   The deficit has not emerged as a major campaign issue, despite
gloomy prognostications from some economists.
   The Treasury says it will pay $220 billion in gross interest on
the public debt in 1989. But the government also earns interest on
Social Security's trust funds and other reserves. The ``net''
interest cost to taxpayers is estimated at $151.8 billion for 1989.
   But there has been little pressure on Bush or Dukakis to fill in
the blanks of their deficit-reduction promises.
   Bush, who in 1980 derided as ``voodoo economics'' Reagan's
promise to balance the budget while cutting taxes and raising
military spending, now is following in Reagan's footsteps by
promising more tax cuts and hands off Social Security. He vows, ``I
will not raise your taxes, period.''
   His so-called ``flexible freeze'' applies to all government
spending other than Social Security and payment of interest on the
national debt.
   Bush would limit the overall growth of other government spending
to the rate of inflation, with increases in some areas offset by
unspecified cuts elsewhere.
   ``It's a commitment to slow the growth of government spending to
make even better progress in reducing the budget deficit than we
have been doing and are projected to do,'' said Michael J. Boskin, a
Stanford University economics professor and senior Bush adviser.
``Exactly when it would lead to a balanced budget depends on how
well the economy does.''
   Boskin said the annual deficit, which in 1983 was the equivalent
of 6.3 percent of the gross national product, is already down to 3.2
percent of GNP and is headed to 1.8 percent of GNP in 1993 even
without the flexible freeze according to a Congressional Budget
Office forecast.
   To critics who question how Bush will achieve his goal while
exempting Social Security, Boskin said, ``It leaves most of the
budget.'' He said Bush is committed to negotiating spending
restraints with Congress, but ``he doesn't think it's appropriate
that he lay out a detailed fiscal year 1990 budget during the
presidential campaign.''
   Like Reagan, Bush epouses a balanced budget amendment and
line-item veto authority _ Dukakis opposes both _ and says, ``The
most important action we need to take on the budget deficit is to
hold the line on taxing and spending.''
   Dukakis, the Democratic challenger, says, ``No serious candidate
can rule out the possibility of new taxes,'' but says that would
only be as ``a last resort.'' His first resort is tougher tax
enforcement.
   Dukakis, who watched Walter Mondale meet his Waterloo with a 1984
campaign declaration that higher taxes were inevitable, talks of
raising tens of billions of dollars through a one-time tax amnesty
and tougher enforcement. ``This is not a pie-in-the-sky formula,''
says Dukakis, who estimates $110 billion in taxes go uncollected
each year.
   Thomas Herman, a senior deputy issues director for the Dukakis
campaign, said Dukakis hopes to net $10 billion the first year and
$30 billion annually by 1993 from tax cheats.
   ``There are only four ways to reduce the federal budget deficit:
cut spending, increase revenue, lower interest rates and improve
economic performance. We must do all four,'' says Dukakis.
   Dukakis has outlined spending cuts on the Strategic Defense
Initiative and some weapons programs, and promised to make ``tough
choices'' elsewhere in the budget, including unspecified savings on
agriculture, welfare and health care, as well as cutting back
development of a supersonic space plane and paring support for
nuclear fission and fusion research. He rules out Social Security
cuts.
   Alice Rivlin, senior fellow at the Brookings Institution and
former director of the Congressional Budget Office, said, ``Both
candidates have been quite vague about what they would do about the
deficit. Neither has put out any kind of a solid plan to bring the
deficit down.''
   ``The reason for that is there really isn't a good plan which can
avoid an increase in taxes. Nobody wants to dramatize that fact,''
she added.
   Lawrence Chimerine, chairman and chief economist of the WEFA
Group, said Bush would aggravate the deficit with a series of tax
cuts or credits he has promised, from lower taxes on capital gains
to a $1,000 ``toddler tax credit'' for poor families.
   Dukakis might find some savings in military and domestic spending
and bring in more revenues by beefing up the Internal Revenue
Service, ``but we're talking very small numbers,'' said Chimerine.
   Both candidates are counting on lower interest rates to help
reduce the deficit, but that is not necessarily within the
president's powers to deliver.
   ``It's Catch-22,'' said Chimerine. ``You can't get the drop in
interest rates until you put forth a credible program, but
fundamentally the drop in interest rates is essentially what their
program is.''
   David Keating, executive vice president of the National Taxpayers
Union, said, ``Bush's flexible freeze could work if he could get
Congress to follow it. But every time the vice president is in a
debate or public forum, he seems to come up with another spending
program.''
   Economist Michael Evans said both candidates are ``up a tree'' in
their quest for lower interest rates.
   ``Interest rates are likely to rise if the deficit rises. The Fed
(Federal Reserve Board) is going to have to defend the dollar next
year, and that's going to push the deficit higher,'' he predicted.
The Fed often raises interest rates to defend the dollar, but this
would also drive up the government's own borrowing costs and
increase the deficit.
   Evans said no one should take comfort from the fact that the
annual deficits have not yet derailed the 70-month-old economic
recovery.
   ``It's like that old line: `This is the way the world will end,
not with a bang but a wimper.' The deficit reduces our growth and
productivity. It diverts our assets to foreign investors,'' said
Evans. ``Just gradually the standard of living erodes.''
   Stephen Moore, an economic policy analyst at the conservative
Heritage Foundation, said the deficit already has come down from a
high of $220 billion two years ago.
   Economic growth is pushing up tax revenues by $60 billion a year,
and ``if you can hold the rate of spending increases to 4 percent a
year, the budget would be balanced in 1993,'' he said. ``I don't
think there's any reason to raise taxes whatsoever.''
   Rivlin said the deficit is even worse than it looks on paper,
because it is masked in part by the growth of Social Security's
trust funds. Those funds now are rising by $40 billion a year and by
the early 1990s will be piling up $100 billion annual surpluses.
   ``We ought to be aiming for a budget surplus by the end of the
1990s because we need more national savings,'' said Rivlin.
   Rivlin said the flexible freeze idea ``sounds good, but when you
look at it, it means Medicare and Medicaid would have to be cut
substantially or you'd have to cut a lot of other spending.'' The
big health care programs have been growing at twice the rate of
inflation in recent years, she said.
   While Bush has said cutting the capital gains tax rate from its
current maximum of 28 to 33 percent down to a flat 15 percent will
actually raise revenues, not lower them, the Congressional Budget
Office has estimated it will cost $3.9 billion a year in revenues.
Some estimates are even higher.
   Bush's tax credits for child care would cost nearly $2 billion,
his tax-deferred savings accounts for the middle-class cost $70
million to start and reach $550 million by 1993; his college savings
bonds cost up to $200 million, and a variety of other tax credits
for rural development and the energy industry could cost up to $1
billion more, acording to Democrats on Capitol Hill.
   Both Bush and Dukakis favor extending the research and
development tax credit, at a cost of more than $1 billion a year.
   Boskin said that putting aside the capital gains tax cut, Bush's
other tax breaks would cost only $4 billion a year, or ``less than
one-third of 1 percent of outlays'' in 1993.
   Rivlin said that ``putting back in little special exceptions for
this and that'' could eventually force lawmakers to raise the low
tax rates achieved in the Tax Reform Act of 1986.
   Bush and Dukakis have another excuse for staying mum on deficit
reduction: a bipartisan National Economic Commission already exists
to do some of the dirty work early next year on how to reduce the
deficit.
   Both candidates disavowed a recent statement by the commission's
co-chairman, Robert Strauss, who said the only way to solve the
deficit is to go after Social Security and other entitlements.
   The National Economic Commission could help the country end its
deficit-spending binge of the 1980s, but ``only if the new president
wants it to,'' said Rivlin. ``If the president wants it, he'll have
lots of help.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
