<1ST_LINE>a p BC-Candidates-GutIssues ADV00   11-02 0997</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Candidates-Gut Issues, ADV 00,1021</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>Emotional Issues Rule the Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's been a down and dirty presidential
campaign, from gleeful Democratic denunciations of George Bush in
Atlanta as a wimp to the Republicans' skewering of Michael Dukakis
over crime, the ACLU and his veto of a mandatory Pledge of
Allegiance bill.
   While the dismal tenor of this year's campaign discourse has
elicited groans from past presidents Richard Nixon and Jimmy Carter,
political analysts credit Bush with tapping some of the same
emotional issues that helped Nixon capture the White House in 1968
and 1972 and laid the groundwork for Ronald Reagan's twin landslides
of the 1980s.
   And some experts say it is a serious mistake for the Democrats,
who lost four of the past five presidential elections, to
underestimate the seriousness with which the electorate responds to
emotional appeals to its patriotism or fear of crime.
   The gut issues, symbolic or not, are real issues for many voters.
   ``Politics is a matter of gut responses, otherwise known as
emotions,'' said Roger D. Masters, a Dartmouth University professor
of government.
   ``It's not just media manipulation,'' said Michael Robinson, a
Georgetown University associate professor of government and expert
on media and politics. ``If the Democrats continue to believe that
symbolic issues don't matter, they're going to foul up time and time
again.''
   Stephen Hess, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution, said
the symbolic issues loom larger in this election because ``American
politics, like nature, abhors a vacuum. The candidates seemed quite
deliberately to choose not to face up to the pragmatic issues.''
   Robinson said the race unfolded in a time of economic prosperity
when there were really few differences between the Democrats and
Republicans on dealing with the Soviet Union.
   ``When you subtract the issues of peace and prosperity, you leave
very little, so we are left to fight on those gut issues,'' he said.
   Analyst Kevin Phillips, publisher of the American Political
Report, said, ``The Republicans have replayed the key cultural and
patriotic issues with the swing voters that got the Republican
presidential majority started in 1968 and 1972 and 1980.''
   By flogging the crime spree of Willie Horton, the Massachusetts
lifer who escaped while on a weekend furlough from prison, and
pummeling Dukakis for being a self-proclaimed card-carrying member
of the American Civil Liberties Union, the Bush campaign succeeded
in rekindling in the minds of wavering Reagan Democrats the emotions
that ``pulled them to vote for Republican presidents in earlier
years,'' said Phillips.
   In their final debate Oct. 13, both candidates sounded apologetic
about the low-road campaigning. Bush, recalling the almost non-stop
attacks the Democrats unleashed on him at their July convention in
Atlanta, said, ``I don't want to sound like a kid in the schoolyard
(but) he started it.''
   ``It was both ways,'' said Ben Wattenberg, an American Enterprise
Institute senior fellow. ``Two months ago, the best issue that
Dukakis had on Bush was `wimp' and the best issue Bush had on
Dukakis was `L-word' (liberal).''
   The Republicans ``went after Dukakis on all the L-word stuff,
which they had some nice symbols for _ prison furloughs and Pledge
of Allegiance and ACLU and stuff like that. But it wasn't about
those issues,'' said Wattenberg. ``The reason they played was
because they resonated in terms of 20 years of Democratic party
history as too liberal.''
   ``It's not a small issue. It is haunting this party,'' said
Wattenberg, a Democrat. ``It is which direction the plurality party
in America wants to take the country.''
   On the other hand, the Democrats' wimp charge quickly lost its
punch as Bush emerged from the GOP convention in New Orleans as
``Captain Marvel,'' said Wattenberg.
   Phillips said, ``By going hard-line on the cultural and patriotic
issues, Bush drove down the wimp factor. ... Bush put on a bit of a
John Wayne outfit.''
   He added that the Democrats failed to develop rival issues to
appeal to the same swing voters. Bush's highest negative rating in
polls remains the perception that he is too close to the rich and
too far from the middle class.
   But Dukakis has been unable to ``come on hard and tough and use
economic populism and nationalism to get the guys in the bar in the
ethnic sections of Cleveland or your dirt farmer in rural Alabama
angry at the Republicans,'' said Phillips.
   Robinson said, ``In a time of real prosperity, questions of
economic justice and hostility toward big business do not cut it
with the American public.''
   ``You can't pretend that something that is an issue is not an
issue. It hurts the Democrats when they try to dismiss this in some
way as bigotry or tasteless or unAmerican,'' said Robinson.
   ``It is an issue to Americans whether you wear your flag on your
sleeve or whether you wear it on the seat of your pants. Republicans
are not only willing to wear their flag on their sleeves, they're
willing to wear it on their foreheads. The Democrats are willing to
move it off their keister, but they still want to keep it half
covered, and Americans don't like that,'' said the Georgetown
professor.
   Hess invoked a memory of a childhood pastime to explain why
emotional issues have been so prominent in this race.
   ``You could compare the whole of American campaigns to the
children's game of rock, paper and scissors,'' he said. ```Rocks are
always the politics-ain't-beanbag issues, the tough gut, hard
campaign. That's always there in American politics.
   ``But it's covered when there are particularly attractive
candidates. Candidates that catch the imagination are
paper-covering-rock. When you have overarching issues _ war or
peace, prosperity or recession _ that's scissors. That cuts paper,''
he explained.
   ``Here we've got a campaign in which there are no overarching
issues, so take away scissors. There are no attractive candidates,
so take away paper.
   ``What are you left with? Rock.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
