<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0548</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rales brothers have won a major victory in
their hostile $2.7 billion bid for Interco Inc., with a court
issuing a preliminary injunction blocking the furniture and apparel
company's poison-pill takeover defense.
   But St. Louis-based Interco said shortly after Tuesday's
announcement that it would appeal the Delaware Chancery Court ruling
and seek a stay to prevent the Raleses from actually acquiring any
shares under their tender offer until a decision is rendered.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Analysts are not overly optimistic about Sears'
plan to shift its merchandising strategy in an attempt to regain
lost profits.
   The 102-year-old Sears, Roebuck and Co. announced Monday it was
switching to a policy of everyday low pricing and away from the
``regular'' prices and frequent sales it has been known for.
   Observers said Tuesday that even with the low-price strategy, it
will take a while for the retailer to change its image.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The losses of the savings industry dropped
sharply in the July-September quarter from $3.6 billion to about $2
billion, according to an industry trade group.
   James Barth, chief economist of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board,
estimated Tuesday that the nation's 3,048 savings institutions lost
$3.9 billion in the first three months of this year and $3.6 billion
in the second quarter.
   Final figures on the third quarter aren't due until early
December, but Barth said the loss should be about $2 billion, the
best showing in a year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 victims of the 1984 Bhopal gas
disaster marched to the U.S. Embassy urging President Reagan to
intervene in the legal battle with Union Carbide Corp. over disaster
relief.
   The rally Tuesday came as the Supreme Court began hearing appeals
on the award of $192 million in interim relief to the victims of the
disaster that killed more than 3,100 people.
   The marchers presented a memorandum to embassy officials that
urged Reagan to ``seriously ponder over the issue and stand by the
side of great human sufferings by upholding the values established
by...George Washington and Abraham Lincoln.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. plans to halt
production of its slow-selling LeBaron GTS and Dodge Lancer car
models in March.
   The company said Tuesday it would shift production to making the
more popular Plymouth Sundance and Dodge Shadow cars.
   Just 8 percent of the cars coming off the assembly line now at
the plant are the four-door LeBaron and Lancer models, called H-cars
by Chrysler. The rest are Shadows and Sundances, the company's P-car
line.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This year's drought is expected to reduce 1988
production of dry beans by 25 percent to the lowest level in five
years, the Agriculture Department says.
   A USDA report also said Tuesday the drought had a substantial
impact' on the output of snap beans, sweet corn, and green peas for
processing as crops withered in Wisconsin, Minnesota, Michigan and
Illinois.
   In addition, the report forecast a lower potato crop this year
because of poor summer and fall harvests stemming from the drought.
</TEXT>
