<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0522</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government report provides further evidence
the economy is slowing, but some economists say it does not signal a
recession.
   The Commerce Department said Tuesday that its chief economic
forecasting gauge _ the Index of Leading Indicators _ dipped 0.1
percent in September, the third decline in the past five months.
   The decline followed drops of 0.7 percent in both May and July.
Often, three consecutive monthly declines have been the signal of an
impending recession.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending climbed 0.6 percent in
September as strength in housing and a rebound in government
building offset weakness in non-residential construction, the
government reports.
   Spending for new construction rose to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of $403.4 billion following a 0.2 percent decline in
August, the Commerce Department said Tuesday.
   Even with the latest increase, construction activity has been
sluggish this year, due to weaknesses in apartment, office and
shopping center construction. Analysts said they expect this pattern
to continue through next year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Department of Justice has approved
the federal government's share of a $226 million settlement between
14 Washington state utilities and purchasers of bonds that were sold
to build two defunct nuclear-power plants.
   U.S. District Judge William Browning was expected to be asked to
sever the utilities from the case, involving the $2.25 billion bond
default by the Washington Public Power Supply System.
   That would leave Snohomish County Public Utility District as the
sole remaining utility defendant.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public Service Co. of New Hampshire
tentatively has agreed to make the Seabrook nuclear power plant
payments that another major owner refuses to make.
   As part of the deal, the utility said Tuesday that all past and
present Seabrook owners would agree not to sue Public Service over
its management of the $5.7 billion project.
   Public Service is operating under federal bankruptcy law
protection because of the stalled Seabrook nuclear plant.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Federal Aviation Administration
says both pilots and air traffic controllers have to improve their
techniques of communicating with each other.
   FAA Administrator Allan McArtor said Tuesday his agency was
issuing a 44-page booklet with ``common sense tips'' and holding
seminars on effective communications between controllers and pilots.
   He said there are too many instances in which pilots or
controllers misunderstand each other because of garbled
communications, use of improper phraseology, improper voice
inflection, poor listening habits and a failure of pilots to read
back clearances given by controllers.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against most major currencies on Tuesday. Gold
prices declined.
   The stock market finished mixed. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials rose 2.31 points to close at 2,150.96.
   Crude oil futures prices declined while platinum futures soared
more than $12 a troy ounce and copper rose. Cattle futures slid;
pork futures were mostly higher; and grains and soybeans were mixed.
</TEXT>
