<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     11-02 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leading Indicators Dip 0.1 Percent; Dollar Declines</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be led with Commerce Department's reports on September
factory orders and new home sales and Labor Department report on
third-quarter labor productivity, all scheduled for late morning EST
release.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A drop 0.1 percent drop in the government's chief economic
forecasting gauge indicates continued slow growth in the economy,
but economists say they do not expect a recession anytime soon.
   The Commerce Department's report Tuesday on its Leading Economic
Indicators helped pressure the dollar lower, but seemed to have
little effect on the stock market.
   The dollar weakened Tuesday despite concerted dollar purchases by
the central banks of the United States and Japan, and that helped
push bonds down slightly.
   Stocks were little changed Tuesday. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials rose 2.31 points to 2,150.96, while declining issues
outnumbered advances by about 8 to 7 on the New York Stock Exchange.
   In other reports Tuesday, the Commerce Department said
construction spending rose 0.6 percent in September to an annual
rate of $403.4 billion as strength in housing and government
construction offset a decline in office building.
   Construction spending for the first nine months of the year is
0.7 percent higher than a year ago, a sluggish performance that
analysts expect will continue because of widespread overbuilding of
offices and other commercial space.
   The drop in the leading indicators was the third in the past five
months.
   ``There is absolutely no question that the economy is slowing
down,'' said Lawrence Chimerine, chief economist of the Wefa Group,
an economic consulting firm. ``The only question is whether this
slowdown will lead into a recession.''
   Chimerine said he believed a recession can be avoided over the
next 12 months to 18 months, although he said this forecast could
prove too optimistic if consumer spending slows more than expected
or if the dollar comes under further pressure from foreigners
worried about the ability of the next administration to deal with
budget and trade deficits.
   The recovery from the 1981-82 recession completes a peacetime
record of six years this month and the Reagan administration is
hoping this performance will persuade voters to keep the White House
in Republican hands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
