<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     11-02 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices have turned mixed, with
home heating oil rising on seasonal demands and other crude oil
products losing ground.
   The December contract for wholesale heating oil was up 0.42 cent
a gallon to settle at 43.17 cents Tuesday on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, after falling 0.71 cent on Monday. Other contract months
also rose.
   Among other petroleum products traded on the exchange Tuesday,
unleaded gasoline, which slipped 1.52 cents on Monday, fell another
0.71 cent to 43.62 cents a gallon.
   The December contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude, settled at $13.44 a barrel, down 14 cents. The contract
was off 27 cents in the previous session.
   John O'Connell, a senior energy analyst for Refco Inc., said
increased seasonal demand and technical factors largely were
responsible for Tuesday's rise in home heating oil prices. But he
said continued worries about overproduction among OPEC members,
particularly giant producer Saudi Arabia, kept other prices down.
   O'Connell said trading was thin as most dealers were reluctant to
take any major positions until the cartel held its scheduled meeting
later this month.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries plans to meet
in Vienna on Nov. 17 to discuss tightening production to boost
sagging worldwide oil prices.
</TEXT>
