<DOCNO> AP881102-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 0044EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TennecoSale     11-02 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tenneco Sale,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tenneco Announces Plans to Sell Louisiana Intrastate Gas Corp.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tenneco Inc. is selling its Louisiana Intrastate
Gas Corp. pipeline business, which it purchased three years ago for
more than $500 million.
   Tuesday's announced sale, expected to be completed by next
spring, is part of a restructuring move prompted by last month's
$7.3 billion sale of the company's Tenneco Oil Co. subsidiary.
   Tenneco officials did not disclose the anticipated sale price for
the business.
   LIG, an affiliate of Tenneco Gas Pipeline Group, operates
approximately 1,900 miles of intrastate gas pipelines for deliveries
into Louisiana's industrial heartland.
   The Louisiana affiliate contributed about $10.3 million in
pre-tax revenue to Tenneco in 1987, said spokeswoman Suzanne Thomas.
   James L. Ketelsen, chairman of the board and chief executive
officer, said Tenneco acquired LIG in 1985 primarily to secure
access to makets for gas production from Tenneco Oil.
   ``With the sale of Tenneco Oil Company, ownership of these
properties is no longer strategically important,'' he said.
   LIG has an average daily pipeline flow of 650 million cubic feet
and serves more than 75 customers, including agricultural and
industrial plants, electric utilities, local distribution companies
and paper mills, Ms. Thomas said.
   The sale will not affect Tenneco's other interstate or intrastate
natural gas pipeline businesses, company officials said. The company
operates approximately 20,000 miles of pipeline in a 26-state market
area, Ms. Thomas said.
   The company said it expects to identify a buyer by the end of
1988 and close the deal no later than March 31, 1989.
   Tenneco is a diversified industrial corporation with major
business interests in natural gas pipelines, farm and construction
equipment, automotive parts, shipbuilding, packaging, chemicals and
minerals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881102-0279 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 0045EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UtilityMerger     11-02 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Utility Merger,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Utah Power, PacifiCorp Directors Reaffirm Merger Support</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of Utah Power & Light Co. and
PacifiCorp have signaled their acceptance of federal conditions
imposed on a proposed $2 billion merger of the utility holding
companies, although they do not necessarily like them, a spokesman
says.
   Directors unanimously reaffirmed their support for a proposed
merger on Tuesday, and extended until Dec. 15 the previous Oct. 31
deadline for either company to terminate the merger if not closed by
the deadline.
   The stock swap merger was approved in August 1987 by both
companies and state regulators in seven states later concurred.
   However, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission last week gave
its approval on condition that the merged company's transmission
lines were opened to competing utilities to ensure the merger would
not be anticompetitive.
   ``From this you can infer that the companies will accept the
conditions the FERC said it will impose, although we think that some
of the conditions are unnecessary and harsh...specifically,
transmission access,'' Utah Power spokesman Dave Mead said.
   Officials of Portland-based PacifiCorp said that while not all
the FERC conditions were believed to be justified, they will not
have a significant effect on the vast majority of merger benefits.
Those include savings from administrative combinations, work force
reductions and meeting peak demand requirements more efficiently.
   Power supply benefits relating to more efficient use of
generating resources between the two companies also remain intact
under the conditions.
   Mead said the merger still was expected to gain Utah customers a
5 percent to 10 percent rate reduction over a four-year period.
   ``Our best estimate is that the FERC transmission conditions will
reduce wholesale power benefits by approximately $1 million annually
for the first five years following the merger,'' said Dave Bolender,
president of PacifiCorp's Pacific Power & Light division.
   ``The primary purpose of the merger is to strengthen our ability
to offer an attractive, competitively priced array of energy
services to our retail customers in an increasingly competitive
marketplace,'' he said. ``The FERC order will not detract from our
ability to compete in that changed marketplace.''
   Utah's Public Service Commission issued an order suspending its
approval of the merger and scheduled a Nov. 8 hearing on the effect
of the FERC's order. Mead said UP&L would present its analysis of
the conditions affecting the merger at that time and were optimistic
about regaining the PSC's approval.
   The merged utility would become one of the largest utilities in
the West, serving more than 1 million customers in a seven-state
service area that also includes Oregon, California, Washington,
Idaho, Montana and Wyoming.
   The FERC expressed concern the merger would stifle competition in
the Western states wholesale power market with a single utility
owning strategic transmission stretching from the Northwest to the
Southwest.
   From the onset, both utilities said that integrating their
transmission systems would provide huge benefits and profits as they
used the merged system to sell excess capacity to lucrative markets
in the Southwest and ``wheel'' power between divisions to stabilize
seasonal periods of low and high demand.
   But FERC's approval requires the merged company to open its
transmission to competing utilities and meet ``all bona fide
requests for service either by using its existing capacity or by
building new facilities.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
