<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0257</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was lower in early trading
today, pressured by the dollar's persistent decline against major
currencies.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 1.07 points at
2,149.89 at 11 a.m. EST.
   Declining issues edged out advancing ones by around 7 to 5 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 669 issues down, 464 up and 565
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 46.84 million shares.
   For the third straight day, the Federal Reserve was said to have
intervened in the foreign-exchange market to bolster the dollar by
buying the U.S. currency.
   Activity continues to be dampened by the market's anticipation of
upcoming events: notably Friday's release of U.S. unemployment data
for October and the presidential election next Tuesday.
   Wall Street appeared to shrug off the report today that new
factory orders fell 1.9 percent in September.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks had
slipped 0.27 to 156.71.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was up
0.28 at 299.84.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Eastman Kodak had
dropped 1\ to 46\, Sears Roebuck was down ] at 41], Ford Motor had
declined \ to 51\, Kraft had slipped [ to 102} and American Express
also had lost [ at 27\.
   RJR Nabisco had risen | to 85|, General Electric was up { at 44\
and Texaco had gained ] at 47\.
