<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Open Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade with soybeans taking the lead
amid indications the Soviet Union was negotiating new purchases of
South American soybean meal.
   Analysts say any indication of new grain or soybean purchases by
the Soviets is generally regarded as bullish for the U.S. markets.
   Analysts said soybean meal values on overseas cash markets were
slightly higher this morning, which added to the stronger tone in
Chicago.
   Soybean oil futures also opened higher but Dale Gustafson, grain
market analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago, said,
``I think it's the interest in the meal providing the underlying
strength for beans.''
   Wheat futures opened mixed and corn was marginally higher. Both
of those markets were awaiting confirmation of rumored new export
business, Gustafson said.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent lower to 1{ cents higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.18 a bushel; corn was {
cent to 1 cent higher with December at $2.85{ a bushel; oats were
unchanged to 1\ cents higher with December at $2.32{ a bushel;
soybeans were 2 cents to 7} cents higher with November at $7.84{ a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent lower to .07 cent higher with December
at 73.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .25 cent
higher with November at 81.80 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent
lower to .38 cent higher with December at 41.80 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .25 cent to .53 cent higher with February
at 47.10 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled lower on Tuesday while pork futures were
mostly higher.
</TEXT>
