<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was higher in midday trading
today after an initial decline.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 6.05 points at
2,157.01 at noon EST. The blue-chip indicator had been down about a
point an hour earlier.
   Advancing issues narrowly edged out declining ones on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 615 issues up, 595 down and 601 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 73.38 million shares, close to
the 73.98 million traded by the same time on Tuesday.
   Activity continues to be dampened by the market's anticipation of
upcoming events: notably Friday's release of U.S. unemployment data
for October and the presidential election next Tuesday.
   ``People are on the sidelines looking towards Friday,'' said
Philip Puccio, a senior vice president of Dillon, Read & Co.
   Wall Street appeared to shrug off the report today that new
factory orders fell 1.9 percent in September.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks had
edged up 0.16 to 157.14.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was up
0.41 at 299.97.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Reebok had jumped 1
point to 14, RJR Nabisco was up { at 85{, General Electric had risen
| to 44], Texaco had gained } at 47| and Kraft was up \ at 103[.
   Eastman Kodak had dropped 1[ to 46], Sears Roebuck was down [ at
41| and Ford Motor was unchanged at 51{.
