<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WPPSSTrial 1stLd-Writethru   11-02 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-WPPSS Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0021,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Drops All But One Utility In WPPSS Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOPS with 4 new grafs with trial reconvening. Picks up 3rd
graf, Browning's order ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only one utility defendant remains in the
securities fraud trial stemming from the Washington Public Power
Supply System's record $2.25 billion municipal bond default.
   District Judge William Browning signed an order Tuesday dropping
14 Washington state utilities from the trial.
   As the trial reconvened today, Browning told the jurors that 14
utilities had settled but instructed them not to infer anything from
the settlement.
   ``You should not consider it,'' the judge instructed. ``You
should not draw any inference of any party.''
   Browning's order came hours after the U.S. Department of Justice
in Washington, D.C., approved the federal government's share of a
$226 million settlement between the utilities and purchasers of
municipal bonds used to build two WPPSS nuclear power plants that
were abandoned before completion.
   Browning still must approve the settlement. A hearing on that
matter is to be scheduled.
   The settlement leaves Snohomish County Public Utility District as
the sole utility defendant in the trial.
   Snohomish has until Nov. 10 to join in the settlement by
approving a $48.6 million offer, said Mel Weiss, an attorney for the
plaintiff bond purchasers.
   The trial will now take on a new complexion with the other
utilities gone, he said.
   The plaintiffs will have to focus on the three other remaining
defendants: Ebasco Services Inc. and United Engineers & Contractors
Inc., two engineering companies that built the unfinished plants,
and Blyth Eastman Paine Webber Inc., a WPPSS financial adviser.
   ``The professional parties haven't been our main focus up to
now,'' Weiss said. ``There will be a greater concentration of effort
to pinpoint the professionals' involvement.''
   Harlan ``Hank'' Kosmata, a WPPSS liaison with the 88 utilities
that contracted with WPPSS to build the plants, has spent 15 days
testifying about events that led to the default. He was to continue
his testimony today.
   The 17-member jury has heard hours of taped meetings of utility
representatives discussing the plants' funding and construction
problems.
   The three professional defendants are being sued by a class of
more than 24,000 past and present bondholders.
   Chemical Bank of New York, a trustee for bondholders, sued only
the utilities. It will remain in the case as long as Snohomish
remains a defendant.
   The plaintiffs claim that the defendants lied and hid information
that might have discouraged potential investors in the WPPSS
municipal bonds. The defendants deny the charges.
   WPPSS defaulted on the bonds in 1983 after scrapping the plants a
year earlier.
   On Tuesday, the Justice Department approved a $35 million
settlement contribution by Bonneville Power Administration, the
power broker in the Pacific Northwest.
   Boards and commissions for the 14 utilities approved settlement
proposals Monday, bringing their share to $181 million.
   Washington state will add $10 million to the settlement package,
contingent on legislative approval.
   There were more than 100 defendants in the fraud suit, but
settlements left only 18 when the trial began Sept. 7. The trial,
moved to Arizona because of pretrial publicity, was expected to last
up to a year.
   A total of $591 million in settlements plus $96 million in
disputed insurance have been reached.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
