<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Wickes     11-02 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Wickes,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Buyer May Sell Retail, Credit Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prospective buyers of Wickes Cos. say they
are considering breaking up the company and selling retail and
credit operations, including Wickes Furniture and Builders Emporium,
if their bid succeeds.
   The Blackstone Group and Wasserstein, Perella & Co., New York
investor groups which launched a $538.9 million buyout Tuesday,
disclosed their intent to sell parts of the company in a filing with
the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   The takeover, negotiated with management, will be accomplished
through an $11.25 per share tender offer to stockholders.
   ``The purchaser expects to sell a significant amount of the
company's assets,'' according to a registration statement for the
tender offer. ``Based on information currently available to it, the
purchaser expects to sell most or all of the company's retail and
credit operations.''
   The statement says the tentative decision to sell various
operations may be reversed or altered.
   The retailers, Wickes Furniture, Builders Emporium home
improvement stores, and Orchard Supply Hardware stores, accounted
for about 31 percent of the company's sales last year. The credit
operations offer financing for the retail stores.
   Wickes other operations include automotive products, wallpaper,
fabrics and the Kayser-Roth hosiery and apparel units.
   Blackstone and Wasserstein, Perella executives will replace
Sanford Sigoloff, the Wickes chairman who saved the company from
bankruptcy and sought to take it private in a leveraged buyout that
led to the investor groups' successful takeover bid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
