<DOCNO> AP881102-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 1359EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SouthlandSale     11-02 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Southland Sale,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convenience Store Chain Selling 70 San Antonio-Area Stores to NCS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Convenience Stores Inc. said Wednesday it
has agreed to buy at least 79 San Antonio-area Southland Corp.
stores for an undisclosed amount of cash.
   The sale, which is still subject to a definitive agreement, is
expected to close in January 1989, officials said.
   ``While our stores in San Antonio are good stores in a good
market, we made this decision after long and careful consideration
of what will help us best achieve our longterm strategic
objectives,'' said Jere W. Thompson, president and chief executive
officer of Dallas-based Southland.
   ``Along these lines, we are pleased that our stores are being
purchased as an ongoing business, which is very important to us for
the future of our employees,'' Thompson said.
   Houston-based NCS, which operates Stop N Go stores, operates
approximately 1,080 specialty retail stores in five Sunbelt states.
   Southland is the world's largest convenience retailer, with more
than 7,000 7-Eleven and other convenience stores that are supported
by Southland's distribution and food centers.
</TEXT>
