<1ST_LINE>a f BC-BehindtheWheel Adv12-13   11-02 0939</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Behind the Wheel, Adv 12-13,0969</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 12</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Nov. 12-13 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Off-Roader for The Rich and Famous</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A quick glance at the Range Rover might not excite you.
   But open the door and let the smell of leather waft your way.
Climb up and lounge inside the roomy interior.
   Take the Range Rover out on a tortuous dirt road and revel in the
oh-so-smooth ride. Head out for the paved highway and marvel at the
lack of road noise.
   This is what a luxury, four-wheel-drive, sport utility vehicle is
all about. The British have known this since 1970, when the Range
Rover _ a descendant of the hearty Land Rover _ was introduced.
   Since the Range Rover's U.S. debut in March 1987, it has been
winning hearts here, too. Range Rover passed its own target of 3,000
sales in its first 12 months in this country, posting sales of 3,350
by March 1988.
   A recent survey of Range Rover buyers showed a startling 95
percent would buy the vehicle again and 98 percent would recommend
one to a friend. Don't think Range Rover buyers aren't selective.
   We're talking actors Tom Cruise and Don Johnson, comedian Tracey
Ullman and band leader Doc Severinsen among the thousands of buyers.
British royalty also are Range Rover fans.
   Average household income of buyers is $200,000-plus and average
age is 43.5 years. Range Rover says a majority pay cash for the
vehicle, which starts at approximately $35,000.
   The company says purchasers also have active lifestyles, meaning
trips to beach houses, fishing, hunting, skiing excursions, etc.
   Twenty-five percent of the primary drivers are female. Nearly
everything you'd expect in a luxury sedan is standard on the Range
Rover: air conditioning, premium AM-FM radio with cassette player
and anti-theft device, cruise control and power seats and windows,
for example.
   The only options are leather upholstery ($1,125), sunroof
($1,375) and Beluga black exterior with burled walnut interior trim
($1,500). Yet the vehicle has all the necessities of a sport utility
vehicle _ and more.
   Besides the always-engaged four-wheel-drive, there are
long-travel coil springs at each of the four wheels to give that
smooth ride, even on bumpy dirt roads.
   Besides the high riding perch and high center of gravity, there
are four Michelin tires that were specially designed to bite into
tough terrain and alternatively travel pavement without the whirring
sound often heard in sport utilities.
   Besides a big, aluminum block, General Motors Corp.-designed V-8,
there are four-wheel disc brakes. There's also a toll-free telephone
number to call for help, even if you run out of gas.
   And Range Rover says the three-year, 36,000-mile warranty, which
covers the complete vehicle except tires, is the best in the
industry for a vehicle of this type.
   The test vehicle, a Range Rover in Beluga black with burled
walnut trim on the doors, was one of only 150 limited editions. At
first glance, it looked utilitarian outside, boxy and rather
un-modern.
   Climbing aboard _ you really have to swing up _ it almost felt
like a tank, with a thick steering wheel and the engine rumbling
under the hood. But the image changed once the Range Rover got
moving.
   It was fairly easy to maneuver, didn't seem to need a real wide
turning arc and was capable of taking on almost anything in its path.
   It went up a steep hill of gravel, and down the same hill, with
less effort and stress than I did at the wheel. It went through sand
nearly effortlessly. It traversed gulches with ease.
   It made a believer out of me. On highways and neighborhood
streets, the Range Rover offered a good view in all directions
because of the high riding position.
   Braking was superb for a vehicle of this type. The suspension
offered decent handling, even considering the high center of gravity
which tends to make all sport utility vehicles less stable than
autos.
   The Range Rover has aluminum body panels welded to a steel frame,
so rust problems are kept to a minimum.
   The vehicle can tow up to 7,700 pounds, though 5,000 pounds is
the optimum.
   But even the Range Rover isn't perfect. The driver side doorway
has no handle at the ceiling or window pillar to help the driver
climb aboard. It would have helped, especially on the days I wore a
skirt.
   The engine, while a mighty V-8 that does admirably off-road,
didn't have much pickup. The vehicle kind of lumbered into traffic.
It also slurped fuel. The government rating is 14 miles per gallon,
combined city and highway driving.
   Consumer Reports does not list the Range Rover in its survey of
owner problems.
   Range Rover says it is the first in this ultra-luxury sport
utility market in the United States. About the closest competitors
are a leather-appointed Jeep Cherokee Limited for about $25,000 and
the Jeep Grand Wagoneer for more than $25,000. But that's destined
to change when a $38,850 Laforza sport utility vehicle goes on sale
in the United States.
   It has a body and interior by Italian coachmaker Pininfarin and a
Ford V-8 engine.
   Range Rover, which is not expected to change substantially its
vehicle for the 1989 model year beginning this month, is not
worried. As spokesman Bill Baker said: ``We have an 18-year heritage
of proven performance.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Job, former executive business editor of The
Detroit News, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The Associated
Press. She has covered the automobile industry for six years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Nov. 12-13</NOTE>
