<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 1418EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   11-02 0133</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0138</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with closing figures.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished lower Wednesday on
profit-taking on the London Stock Exchange.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished the
day off 14.6 points, or 0.8 percent, at 1,843.2.
   A relatively light 427.9 million shares were traded, compared
with the 473.6 million shares Tuesday.
   ``There's a sense of frustration around,'' said a market maker
for a large brokerage firm, saying that players were disappointed
with the absence of any new trading impetus.
   In addition, the execution of two large computer-generated sell
programs also cast a negative pall over the market, some market
watchers said.
   The Financial Times 30-share index fell 12.1 points to 1,495.6.
The Financial Times 500-share index fell 7.44 points to 1,050.69 at
the close.
</TEXT>
