<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMer expected by 5:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell Wednesday against nearly all
major currencies in choppy European trading despite reported efforts
by the U.S. and Japanese central banks to support the currency. Gold
bullion prices rose.
   Foreign exchange dealers said bearish sentiment on the dollar
remained strong despite repeated intervention in the market by the
U.S. Federal Reserve and the Bank of Japan. They said the pressure
by the central bank's dollar-buying kept the dollar's slide in
check, however.
   The Bank of Japan has intervened in support of the dollar for
three consecutive days, the dealers said.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.62 Japanese yen to a closing 124.68
yen. Later in London, the dollar edged back up to 124.82 yen.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7740 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.7668 late Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates, compared with Tuesday's late rates,
included: 1.7840 West German marks, down from 1.7865; 1.4975 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5025; 6.0885 French francs, down from 6.0965;
2.0193 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0155; 1,322.00 Italian lire, down
from 1,331.50; and 1.2275 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2278.
   Gold prices surged amid buying interest from the Middle East and
a sharp rise in platinum prices, dealers said.
   In London, gold rose to a late bid of $417.20 a troy ounce from
$411.25 late Tuesday. In Zurich, gold rose to $417 an ounce from
$411 late Tuesday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $413.90 an ounce, up from
$413.89 at Tuesday's close.
   Silver bullion jumped in London to a late bid of $6.45 a troy
ounce, up from $6.28 late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
