<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Insurance,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Travelers Reports 8 Percent Increase in Net Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Travelers Corp. on Wednesday reported its
third-quarter earnings rose 8 percent as the insurance company's
revenue increased 2 percent.
   Travelers said it earned $91 million, or 89 cents per share, in
the quarter ended Sept. 30, up from $84 million, or 79 cents per
share, in the same period a year ago.
   Total third-quarter revenue was $4.4 billion, compared to $4.3
billion in the same period of 1987.
   ``Third-quarter results benefitted from continued strong earnings
from our property-casualty commercial line operations,'' Edward H.
Budd, chairman and chief executive officer, said in a statement.
   ``While health-insurance claim costs continue to increase
rapidly, substantial price increases are taking effect and results
improved for the quarter,'' Budd said. ``The company is continuing
to implement major cost-saving programs across all operations.''
   For the first nine months of the year, the company reported a
loss of $175 million, compared to net income of $332 million, or
$3.19 per share, for the first nine months of 1987.
   The loss reflected the impact of the $415 million addition to
reserves for real estate operations in the second quarter.
   For the first nine months, total revenue was $14.9 billion,
compared to $13.9 billion for the first nine months of 1987.

