<HEAD>Soybeans Close Up Sharply On Soviet-Buying Talk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply higher
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade in response to rumors that
the Soviet Union had made a large purchase of U.S. soybeans or
soybean meal and was planning to buy more.
   Rumors about Soviet buying also fueled moderate gains in the corn
market, analysts said. Wheat closed mostly higher in quiet trading.
   Analysts said there were indications the Soviets also may have
purchased soybeans from Brazil or Argentina.
   The rumors did not indicate how the Soviet purchases broke down
by country of origin. But of the overall amount, ``the talk is about
500,000 (metric) tons with more bids being put out overnight,'' said
Mario Balletto, soybean analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets
Inc. in New York.
   Soybeans for delivery in November traded during the session to $8
a bushel for the first time since Oct. 20 but ended slightly below
that level.
   The Soviets also were said to have purchased 1.5 million to 2
million metric tons of U.S. corn, said Dale Gustafson, an analyst
with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   At the close, wheat was 1\ cents to 2\ cents higher with December
at $4.19} a bushel; corn was { cent to 3 cents higher with December
at $2.87} a bushel; oats were 1{ cents lower to \ cent higher with
December at $2.32{ a bushel; soybeans were 7{ cents to 22} cents
higher with November at $7.99{ a bushel.
