<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 1911EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Schering-ICN     11-02 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Schering-ICN,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>German Firm Says U.S.-Based ICN Company Targeting Its Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schering AG has been informed that
U.S.-based ICN Pharmaceuticals Inc. intends to amass up to 25
percent of the West German company, a Schering spokesman said
Wednesday.
   The spokesman said ICN has told Schering it intends to acquire
and hold $15 million worth of the common stock in the
pharmaceuticals and chemicals group, which would amount to about 1
percent of its outstanding shares, and may later increase the
holding up to 25 percent.
   Ralph Harenberg, Schering's spokesman, said the company considers
ICN's bid for its shares as a hostile offer.
   ``Schering AG has notified ICN Pharmaceuticals that Schering
regards any sizable purchase of its stock as unwelcome,'' the German
company said in a statement.
   There was no answer at the Costa Mesa, Calif. office of an ICN
spokesman when a reporter called for comment.
   Harenberg said Schering's largest shareholder, the insurance
giant Allianz AG, holds 6 percent of its shares. The rest of the
shares are held by about 42,000 individual investors.
   He said ICN's bid will be blocked by his company's voting rights
limitation that restricts the execution of voting rights to a 4.2
percent stake.
   ``We don't believe a takeover is possible,'' Harenberg said.
   The voting rights limitation ``clearly demonstrates the desire of
Schering's stockholders to assure a wide distribution of Schering's
stock,'' the company statement said.
   ICN, which had $121 million in sales last year, approached
Schering in late September with an offer to purchase an unspecified
stake in the German company, but the offer was rejected, Harenberg
said.
   He said the company initially learned of ICN's actions from a
request by the U.S. Federal Trade Commission, which asked Schering
for the stock data after ICN had registered with the FTC its intent
to seek a stake in the German company valued at 15 million dollars.
</TEXT>
