<DOCNO> AP881102-0299 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 2208EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-ZappingZenith-Brookhurst Adv06   11-02 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Zapping Zenith-Brookhurst, Adv 06,0710</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Nov. 6 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>New York Arbitragers Say They Aren't Ogres</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Zapping Zenith</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New Yorkers who are out to sell Zenith
Electronics Corp.'s television-making business admit their public
image leaves much to be desired.
   In Glenview, Ill., Herbert B. Abelow and Nicholas L. Ihasz are
seen as get-rich-quick artists. In New York, where getting rich
quickly is an honorable pursuit, they are seen as inexperienced.
   In a recent interview in their 41st-floor offices near the New
York Stock Exchange, the men said they are simply exercising their
rights as part-owners of the company.
   ``In the late 1800s, management worked for shareholders. But
management just started to think of the companies as their own
places,'' Abelow said.
   In billion-dollar companies such as Zenith, Abelow said,
ownership is spread so thin that individual shareholders feel they
have no power.
   Meanwhile, he said, directors and managers don't care about
shareholders because they themselves have only tiny stakes in the
company.
   Driving the point home, Brookhurst Partners says its 6.1 percent
stake in Zenith is bigger than the stake of all 27 Zenith directors
and officers combined.
   ``The bottom line is we're investors and shareholders like any
other shareholders,'' Abelow said. ``We're not trying to scrub this
company or junk it or give it away to a foreigner.''
   ``All we're really trying to do is ask the shareholders what
their preferences are,'' Ihasz agreed.
   Abelow and Ihasz say Zenith management has shown no ability or
even serious commitment to make its television business profitable.
   Their goal is to boost the price of Zenith's stock by finding a
buyer for the consumer electronics business or, if no one wants just
that part, to find someone who will buy the whole company.
   That, naturally, is not the way Zenith sees it.
   ``What we have here in part are a couple of guys who say this
appears to be easy,'' said Jerry K. Pearlman, Zenith's chairman and
chief executive. ``Somebody comes along and bails you out and you
have a quick, bing-bing turnover and you've made your reputation.''
   Wall Street analysts would be happy to see someone come along and
boost the value of Zenith's stock. But some say Abelow and Ihasz may
not be the right men for such a job because all their experience
lies in the unrelated field of risk arbitrage _ picking stocks of
potential takeover targets.
   ``There's nothing in the Brookhurst reports which indicates they
understand the details of the business,'' said James Magid, a senior
adviser at Needham & Co. ``That's not who I would hire for the job.
That's a blank check.''
   ``I think that people are now coming to the conclusion that these
people are not the right ones to do it,'' said Robert Johnson, an
analyst for Rotan-Mosle Inc. in Houston.
   Ihasz worked from 1976 to 1980 for Ivan Boesky, the speculator
who is now serving three years in prison, a point that Zenith
delights in pointing out to shareholders.
   Ihasz, prepared for questions about the black spot on his resume,
says he was simply a functionary who had nothing to do with Boesky's
illegal trades.
   ``I was physically distanced from him at all times. ... I left in
1980. I've talked to him maybe twice in the last eight years.''
   Pearlman says he needs more time to carry out his plan for
improving Zenith's profitability, accusing Brookhurst of having its
eye only on short-term profits. That does not sit well with
Brookhurst.
   ``In one of the greatest economic expansions in history, how can
you not be profitable for almost four years?'' Ihasz responded.
``What is long-term? How long do you need?''
   ``We believe in capital formation, all the good things. We're not
against motherhood,'' Abelow said.
   ``I think it would be good probably to have an American producer
(of televisions) ... but I don't consider televisions to be
necessarily a national security item,'' Abelow said.
   Pearlman's bottom line: ``They picked the wrong company.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Nov. 6</NOTE>
