<2ND_LINE>AM-Disney-Unions,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiators Agree on Labor Contract; Union Members Vote Later</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for Walt Disney World
and six unions representing 9,200 workers have reached tentative
agreement on a new labor contract, union officials said Wednesday.
   ``Considering the alternatives, we feel that this is a contract
we can recommend'' to union members, said Harvey Totzke, president
of the unions' Service Trades Council.
   But neither side would disclose details of the pact.
   Union members will vote by ballot on the proposed contract later
this week.
   The council had sought across-the-board wage increases while
Disney was offering a combination of wage hikes and bonuses. Union
members had earlier defeated a Disney offer for a 4 percent wage
increase in the contract's first year, with a 2 percent pay raise
combined with a 2 percent bonus in each of the pact's final two
years.
   ``There are no bonuses'' in the newest agreement, Totzke said.
   Wages now range from $4.85 to $9.70 an hour for union members,
who include food servers, custodians, stagehands, bus drivers, meat
cutters, housekeepers and those who portray the Disney characters.
</TEXT>
