<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     11-02 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0310</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished lower today in mostly
quiet trading, pressured by the dollar's persistent slide against
other major currencies.
   After seesawing gently up and down through most of the session,
stocks took a sudden downturn in the early afternoon. Analysts
attributed the move mainly to the dollar, which fell despite a third
straight day of dollar purchases in the open market by the Federal
Reserve.
   Stock investors are nervous that the dollar's decline could move
the Fed to bolster the currency by nudging interest rates higher.
Many market watchers had been anticipating stable interest rates
recently, as the economy showed signs of slowing down.
   The U.S. currency's fall is ``making people very, very nervous,''
said Hugh Johnson, senior vice president at First Albany Corp. in
Albany, N.Y. ``It obviously puts enormous pressure on the Federal
Reserve.''
   Stocks also were hit by an upward spike in prices of gold and
other key commodities, analysts said. The commodity price rise
rekindled anxiety about inflationary pressures.
   ``All of a sudden, the long-dormant terror about inflation (was)
revived here,'' said Michael Metz, an analyst for Oppenheimer & Co.
   Through most of the trading day, activity continued to be
dampened by the market's anticipation of upcoming events: notably
Friday's release of U.S. unemployment data for October and the
presidential election next Tuesday.
   ``People are on the sidelines looking towards Friday,'' said
Philip Puccio, a senior vice president of Dillon, Read & Co.
   Wall Street shrugged off today's report that U.S. productivity
rose by an annual rate of 1.3 percent from July through September,
reversing a second-quarter decline.
   The government also reported that factory orders fell 1.9 percent
and sales of new homes declined 7.8 percent in September, signs of a
decelerating economy.
  
</TEXT>
