<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-02 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls; Gold Soars</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar tumbled again Wednesday despite
reported efforts by the U.S. and Japanese central banks to support
the currency.
   Gold prices shot upward. Republic National Bank of New York said
gold bullion was bid at $420.90 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up
sharply from $411.30 an ounce late Tuesday.
   The dollar's fall brought it to a six-month low against the
Japanese yen and five-month lows against other major currencies.
   Traders said dollar purchases by the Bank of Japan and the
Federal Reserve were only partially successful because market
participants felt the central banks were trying to slow the U.S.
currency's fall, not arrest it.
   ``The markets are interpreting this as a smoothing operation,''
said Randy Kaplan, a dealer for National Australia Bank Ltd. in New
York.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.62 Japanese yen to 124.68 yen. Later
in London, the dollar edged back up to 124.82 yen. At the end of the
trading day in New York, the dollar fell to 124.40 yen from 125.07
yen.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7740 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.7668 late Tuesday.
In New York, the pound rose to $1.7805 from $1.7698.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.7750 West German marks, down from 1.7840; 1.4898
Swiss francs, down from 1.4982; 1.2261 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2274; 6.0470 French francs, down from 6.0895; and 1,319.88 Italian
lire, down from 1,325.50.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Tuesday's late
rates, included: 1.7840 West German marks, down from 1.7865; 1.4975
Swiss francs, down from 1.5025; 6.0885 French francs, down from
6.0965; 2.0193 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0155; 1,322.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,331.50; and 1.2275 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2278.
   Gold and silver prices were led upward by a continuing
speculative surge in the price of platinum as well as the dollar's
weakness, said Brian Donohue, a gold trader in New York for Midland
Montagu Metals.
   ``Gold was overdue for a breakout. They've been talking the
metals down so long that a lot of people were caught short,''
Donohue said.
   In Hong Kong, gold closed at $413.90 a troy ounce, up from
$413.89 at Tuesday's close.
   Later in Zurich, gold rose to $417 an ounce from $411 late
Tuesday. In London, gold rose to a late bid of $417.20 a troy ounce
from $411.25 late Tuesday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $421.80 a troy ounce from $411.60 Tuesday.
   Silver bullion jumped in London to a late bid of $6.45 a troy
ounce, up from $6.28 late Tuesday. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery rose to $6.488 a troy ounce from $6.293.
</TEXT>
