<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-02 0804</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0832</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Platinum, Other Precious Metals Soar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices of precious metals futures soared Wednesday as heavy
buying of platinum by the Japanese pushed the metal's price to a
4{-month high and triggered strong rallies in the gold and silver
markets.
   On other markets, copper futures leaped to record highs; soybean
prices surged while grain futures finished mostly higher; livestock
and meat prices were mixed; energy futures were higher and
stock-index futures advanced.
   Platinum for delivery in January settled at $578.60 a troy ounce
on the New York Mercantile Exchange, $15.40 above Tuesday's final
price. The January contract's price reached $582.50 during the
session, the highest price for a nearby platinum contract since June
21, when July platinum traded at $592 a troy ounce.
   Platinum has been rising steadily since early October, when the
British platinum refiner Johnson Matthey PLC predicted supply
shortfalls this year and for the next four years.
   Analysts attributed Wednesday's unusually strong rally to the
dollar's steep drop against the Japanese yen, which further lowered
the price of platinum in yen terms and sparked heavy Japanese buying
of the physical metal.
   ``They just had a window of opportunity for buying platinum,''
said Sharon Ziemian, a precious metals market analyst with Citibank
in New York.
   The sudden rise widened the gap between platinum's price and that
of lower-priced gold to $160, just $5 short of the all-time high,
said James Steel, metals analyst with Refco Inc. in New York.
   The increase in the platinum-to-gold premium was a strong buy
signal for chart-watching ``technical'' traders, Steel said.
   ``Because platinum was racing away like this, everybody said gold
and silver were now undervalued compared to platinum,'' Steel said.
``That helped lift gold, which in turn helped lift silver.''
   Gold and silver futures settled at their highest levels since
mid-September on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled $10.20 to $12 higher with December at $424.20 a troy
ounce; silver was 19.5 cents to 20.3 cents higher with December at
$6.53 a troy ounce.
   Copper futures rocketed higher on the Comex in response to new
developments in the 2-week-old copper miners' strike in Peru, the
world's seventh-largest copper producer.
   On Wednesday, the Southern Peru Copper Corp., which controls
two-thirds of Peru's copper production, said it was considering
declaring a ``force majeure'' on shipments. Such a declaration would
mean the company was unable to fulfill its delivery obligations. The
company also announced a delay in scheduled shipments to its
European customers.
   Copper settled 1.40 cents to 5.10 cents higher with the spot
November contract at $1.535 a pound and the more active December
contract at $1.463 a pound.
   Soybean futures prices finished sharply higher on the Chicago
Board of Trade in response to rumors that the Soviet Union had made
a large purchase of U.S. soybeans or soybean meal and was planning
to buy more.
   Talk of Soviet buying also fueled moderate gains in the corn
market, analysts said. Wheat closed mostly higher in quiet trading.
   Analysts said there were indications the Soviets also may have
purchased soybeans from Brazil or Argentina.
   The rumors did not indicate how the Soviet purchases broke down
by country of origin. But of the overall amount, ``the talk is about
500,000 (metric) tons with more bids being put out overnight,'' said
Mario Balletto, soybean analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets
in New York.
   After the close, the Agriculture Department said the Soviets had
purchased 250,000 metric tons of U.S. soybeans and that another
250,000 metric tons had been sold to unknown destinations.
   Wheat settled \ cent to 1\ cents higher with December at $4.18} a
bushel; corn was \ cent to 1} cents higher with December at $2.86{ a
bushel; oats were 1{ cents to 2{ cents lower with December at $2.30{
a bushel; soybeans were 3\ cents to 18{ cents higher with November
at $7.95\ a bushel.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle settled .05 cent
lower to .32 cent higher with December at 73.62 cents a pound;
feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .08 cent higher with November
at 81.65 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent to .52 cent higher
with December at 41.75 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .38
cent to .80 cent higher with February at 47.35 cents a pound.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, West Texas Intermediate
crude oil settled 23 cents to 31 cents higher with December at
$13.75 a barrel; heating oil was .15 cent to .24 cent higher with
December at 43.35 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .08 cent to
.30 cent higher with December at 43.79 cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures rose slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 settled .85 point higher at 281.
</TEXT>
