<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 1814EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Interco     11-02 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Interco,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Stays Order Enjoining Interco Poison Pill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delaware court on Wednesday temporarily halted
the Rales brothers from proceeding with their hostile $2.7 billion
bid for Interco Inc., giving the furniture and apparel company a
chance to appeal a ruling knocking down its poison pill.
   The Delaware Chancery Court granted a stay of its decision
Tuesday to issue a preliminary injunction blocking the company's
poison pill on grounds that it had been improperly used.
   St. Louis-based Interco has said it would appeal. Unless the
ruling is reversed, the brothers are almost certain to win their
4-month-old battle for Interco.
   The Washington, D.C.-based Rales brothers, through Cardinal
Acquisition Corp., have a $74-a-share tender offer outstanding that
is due to expire at midnight Wednesday. It is certain to be
extended, since they are prevented from purchasing any shares while
the stay is in effect.
   But on Wednesday, Cardinal announced that more than 29 million
Interco shares had been tendered. Those shares, coupled with the
Rales's previous holdings, represent 91 percent of the company's
outstanding stock.
   A source close to the Raleses called the stay ``a temporary
setback'' for the brothers. ``The court simply agreed to give more
time to Interco.''
   The Raleses own 8.7 percent of Interco's stock. Their offer is
subject to 75 percent participation among Interco's 36.2 million
shares outstanding as well as the withdrawal of the poison-pill
shareholder rights plan.
   Cardinal, which opened the bidding for Interco at $64 a share
last July, increased its hostile offer from $70 a share to $74 two
weeks ago.
   Several attorneys have remarked on the significance of the
court's original action in blocking the pill. Robert Kohl, a partner
in the New York office of Gaston & Snow, noted that the case
``involves the limits on the strategic use of the pill in the whole
takeover process.''
   The message is that a company cannot use the poison pill as a
defense to preserve its own restructuring while a similar offer is
on the table from an unwanted suitor.
   Interco adopted a poison pill in 1985 but revised it in July
after noticing unusual trading activity in its stock. Days later,
Interco Chairman Harvey Saligman announced he would recommend a
major restructuring.
   In September, Interco countered the Rales's buyout overtures with
a multibillion-dollar defensive restructuring plan valued at $76 a
share, including a special $25-a-share cash dividend to shareholders.
   Kohl noted, however, that the Interco restructuring ``had a lot
of funny money in it _ besides cash, there are three kinds of debt,
one kind of preferred stock and one stub stock. It's very hard for a
board to say that $74 in cash is wholly inadequate and $76 in funny
money is adequate.''
   Kohl speculated that if the Interco restructuring had been valued
$20 higher than the Rales's offer, Chancellor William T. Allen might
have decided differently.
   In active trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Interco fell 75
cents to close at $71 a share.
   Interco manufactures men's and women's apparel, footwear,
furniture and home furnishings. Among the company's main brands are
London Fog rainwear, Ethan Allen furniture and Florsheim shoes.
   Company sales for the first half of the current fiscal year were
$1.27 billion, up 3 percent from 1987.
</TEXT>
