<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0643</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS new grafs 17-18 with updated closing prices; picks up
17th graf pvs bg'ng, Standard & ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished mixed in seesaw trading
Wednesday, pressured by the dollar's persistent slide against other
major currencies.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.87 points to
2,156.83. The blue-chip indicator had been down more than 10 points
at 2:30 p.m. EST.
   The broader market ended lower. Declining issues edged out
advances by around 4 to 3 on the New York Stock Exchange, with 842
issues down, 598 up and 543 unchanged.
   After bobbing up and down through most of the session, stocks
took a sudden brisk downturn in the early afternoon. Analysts
attributed the move mainly to the dollar, which fell despite a third
straight day of dollar purchases in the open market by the Federal
Reserve.
   Stock investors are nervous that the dollar's decline could move
the Fed to bolster the currency by nudging interest rates higher.
Many market watchers had been anticipating stable interest rates
recently, as the economy showed signs of slowing down.
   The U.S. currency's fall is ``making people very, very nervous,''
said Hugh Johnson, senior vice president at First Albany Corp. in
Albany, N.Y. ``It obviously puts enormous pressure on the Federal
Reserve.''
   The dollar was quoted in late New York trading at around 124.40
Japanese yen, down from 125.07 yen late Tuesday.
   Stocks also were hit by an upward spike in prices of gold and
other key commodities, analysts said. The commodity price rise
rekindled anxiety about inflationary pressures.
   ``All of a sudden, the long-dormant terror about inflation (was)
revived here,'' said Michael Metz, an analyst for Oppenheimer & Co.
   Through most of the trading day, activity continued to be
dampened by the market's anticipation of upcoming events: notably
Friday's release of U.S. unemployment data for October and the
presidential election next Tuesday.
   ``People are on the sidelines looking towards Friday,'' said
Philip Puccio, a senior vice president of Dillon, Read & Co.
   Wall Street shrugged off the report that U.S. productivity rose
by an annual rate of 1.3 percent from July through September,
reversing a second-quarter decline.
   The government also reported that factory orders fell 1.9 percent
and sales of new homes declined 7.8 percent in September, signs of a
decelerating economy.
   Once again, there were unsubstantiated rumors in the market of
possible publication of reports that could damage Republican
presidential prospects. This time the rumors centered on vice
presidential candidate Dan Quayle. But they were not as widespread
as two weeks ago and had little or no effect on the market. The
rumor two weeks ago involved Vice President George Bush and was
quickly denied.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE totaled 161.30 million shares, up
from 151.25 million in Tuesday's session. Nationwide, consolidated
volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional
exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled 190.64 million
shares.
   The NYSE's composite index edged up 0.02 to 157.00.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Reebok jumped 1[ to
14[, RJR Nabisco advanced 1} to 86}, Kraft rose | to 103{, General
Motors was up ~ at 84~ and Sears Roebuck gained 1\ at 43.
   American Express was unchanged at 27] and Ford Motor slipped [ to
51].
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 0.11 to 321.35, and S&P's
500-stock composite index was unchanged at 279.06.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was up
0.27 at 299.83. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 381.78, down 0.57.
   The Wilshire Associates Equity Index, the market value of NYSE,
American and OTC issues, was down $3.072 billion.
</TEXT>
