<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 2129EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Doppler-Airports     11-02 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Doppler-Airports,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Awards Contract to Raytheon For Wind Shear Radar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration on
Wednesday awarded a $180 million contract to Raytheon Co. for
installation of special radar equipment to detect wind shears at
major airports beginning in the early l990s.
   Powerful wind shears called microbursts have been the cause of at
least five airline accidents that claimed more than 500 lives in the
last 15 years, including the l985 crash of a Delta Air Lines jet
that killed 137 people near Dallas.
   The contract calls for installation of so-called Doppler radar,
which can detect such shears, at 47 major airports at a cost of $180
million over a number of years.
   The agency also said it has an option for 55 additional radars at
other airports, costing another $100 million, although no final
decision has yet been made to expand the program beyond the original
group of 47 airports.
   FAA spokesman Fred Farrar said the agency could provide no list
of the airports because the location of the radars has yet to be
determined. Agency officials previously have said airports with
heavy traffic loads and susceptibility to wind shears would be given
the greatest priority.
   ``The terminal Doppler system has a greater potential for
realizing safety gains than perhaps any other individual item of
equipment (in the FAA's air traffic modernization program),'' said
Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley in a statement.
   FAA Administrator Allan McArtor said the introduction of the
radar along the approach and departure paths of major airports is
``a major step'' in providing controllers and pilots with better and
quicker adverse weather warnings.
   A wind shear is a sudden change of wind direction that causes a
powerful downburst of air much like water gushing from a faucet. The
downward gust of air is strong enough to literally drive a jetliner
into the ground when it is at a low altitude such as when landing or
departing.
   Under the multiyear contract, Raytheon's Equipment Division at
Wayland, Mass., will provide the first terminal Doppler radar to the
FAA's Technical Center in Atlantic City, N.J., in the fall of l991
with the first radar for airport delivery in late l992, the FAA said.
   The FAA has had mechanical wind monitoring equipment at many
major airports for a number of years, but experts have said the
equipment cannot cover along the entire approach and takoff paths
used by jetliners and, therefore, is of minimal benefit.
   The wind monitors were in use at the Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport when a Delta Air Lines Lockheed L-1011
encountered a powerful microburst during an approach Aug. 2, 1985
causing it to crash and kill 137 people.
   The mechanical monitors also were at the New Orleans airport on
July 9, l982 when a Pan American World Airways jet encountered a
wind shear as it took off. The Boeing 727 crashed, killing 153
people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881102-0312 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 2130EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Coors     11-02 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Coors,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coors Reports 7.5 Percent Profit Increase; Record Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adolph Coors Co. said Wednesday its
third-quarter profit rose 7.5 percent, helped by the company's
recent geographic expansion and healthy growth of Coors Light beer.
   For the three-month period ended Oct. 2, Coors said its after-tax
profit totaled $21.6 million, or 59 cents a share, up from $20.1
million, or 55 cents a share, in the 1987 third quarter.
   The Golden, Colo.-based company said it had record revenue of
$497.95 million for the quarter, up 15 percent from $432.76 million
in the year-ago period.
   Coors said the company's geographical expansion, a 10 percent
increase in Coors Light sales and the addition of new products
accounted for the quarter's gains. Sales in New York, New Jersey,
Pennsylvania and Delaware exceeded expectations, the company said.
   However, Coors profit has risen only a fraction since January due
to high advertising and marketing expenditures, Coors said.
   ``The costs of maintaining a high-visibility advertising and
marketing program, along with costs associated with the 1988 market
expansion and product rollouts, continued to impact earnings,'' said
Coors Chairman William K. Coors.
   For the first nine months of the year, Coors net income totaled
$44.64 million, or $1.22 a share, compared with $44.49 million, or
$1.22 per share, for the same period in 1987. Revenue totaled $1.2
billion, up 9 percent from $1.1 billion in the same 1987 period.
   The company also said it declared a quarterly dividend of 12{
cents a share payable Nov. 15 to shareholders of record on Oct. 31,
1988.
