<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Eagle-Picher     11-02 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Eagle-Picher,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Stock Plunges On Lower Earnings Expectations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eagle-Picher Industries Inc.'s stock price
plunged by nearly half Wednesday after the company said it was
dramatically boosting its provision for asbestos damage claim
liability and as a result would post a big net loss for this year.
   The diversified manufacturing company, which also said it was
suspending its common stock dividend, said the plan would result in
a negative net worth.
   The company's stock tumbled $13.50 to close at $15 a share on the
New York Stock Exchange, a 47 percent drop.
   Eagle-Picher said it would boost its $59 million provision for
current and future asbestos liability by $554 million. The company
also plans to sell three divisions for an estimated $85 million.
   Eagle-Picher said the plan would reduce its earnings per share _
$3.70 in 1987 _ by about $46.70 a share in 1988, and reduce
shareholders equity by $499 million.
   Eagle-Picher posted third quarter net income of $30.7 million, or
$2.87 per share, on revenue of $567.2 million.
   While accounting will indicate a negative net worth on its Nov.
30, 1988 balance sheet, management believes the assets of
Eagle-Picher have a fair value in excess of their book value and
that Eagle-Picher will remain solvent on a fair value basis, the
company said.
   The company, which also said it was suspending its 28 cents a
share quarterly common stock dividend, also plans to keep operating
while it deals with the claims.
   In 1985, there were 8,900 asbestos claims against Eagle-Picher,
11,900 in 1986 and 20,800 in 1987. The company projects that claims
are continuing at about the same rate this year as in 1987.
   The claims stemmed from an asbestos pipe compound Eagle-Picher
produced for the ship building industry, at the request of the
government, beginning in World War II.
   Asbestos has been linked to lung diseases which show up years
after exposure.
   Eagle-Picher said it planned to sell its Bearings, Chi-Vit and
A.D. Weiss Lithograph Co. divisions. Those divisions annually
account for a total $9.6 million in pre-tax earnings and $109
million in revenue.
   Thomas E. Petry, Eagle-Picher president, said the company has had
to re-evaluate its asbestos liability which was established in 1985.
   ``The company is vigorously pursuing both legislative and legal
initiatives to resolve this issue,'' Petry said.
 
</TEXT>
