<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HealthCards     11-02 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Health Cards,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blue Cross To Market Credit Card for Medical Expenses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER BRANDLON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A credit card devoted exclusively to medical and
dental expenses that insurance companies won't cover was unveiled
Wednesday by a subsidiary of Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Maryland.
   Instead of paying by cash or check, patients can use the card to
pay for a school physical examination, a bottleof medicine or the
deductible on a health insurance policy, said Jack Rapport,
president of Health Line Inc., a subsidiary of the insurance company.
   The card, which is called Medcash, can also be used for
preventive health care, such as routine doctor visits, weight-loss
clinics and home blood-pressure kits.
   ``Consumers are paying for these expenses largely out of pocket.
... There's an awful lot of health care that can be purchased that
is not covered by insurance,'' Rapport said.
   Health Line plans to market the card throughout Maryland during
the next year and eventually offer it nationwide through other state
Blue Cross-Blue Shield plans.
   More than 300 health care professionals and hospitals agreed to
accept the card during its test-marketing in Baltimore.
   Most major medical institutions are ``hesitant to accept
commercial or retail credit cards for professional services ...
because of the commercialism that could be associated with that,''
Rapport said. ``(But) Blue Cross-Blue Shield already has an
extensive relationship with virtually all major providers,'' and 85
percent of the providers asked to accept the Medcash card agreed to
do so.
   The company started by offering the card to its employees, and
about 1,000 of them signed up, Rapport said.
   The card, Rapport said, allows patients to separate health care
expenditures from retail purchases and provides a form of insurance
against unforeseen medical expenses. Card holders also can request a
year-end summary of health care spending for their tax records.
   The card offers initial credit of $1,000 to $5,000, with the
possibility of obtaining additional coverage in an emergency by way
of a toll-free telephone number.
   A $24 annual charge will be waived the first year, the company
said.
   No interest will be charged if the balance is paid within 25
days. The company charges 7 percent more than the prime lending rate
on unpaid balances and offers a three-year repayment plan, the
company said. The prime rate is around 10 percent.
   Rapport said the card offers an advantage to health care
providers by cutting the time and money they spend on bill
collection.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
