<DOCNO> AP881102-0318 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 2202EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FCC-LicenseRevoked     11-02 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FCC-License Revoked,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Board Revokes Licenses for Two Georgia Radio Stations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Federal Communications Commission review
board on Wednesday revoked the licenses for two Georgia radio
stations charging that their owner abused the agency's policy on
distress sales to minorities.
   The FCC review board accused Silver Star Communications-Albany
Inc., of ``callous abuse'' of the process that allows a licensee
facing revocation to sell their station to qualified minorities at a
discounted price.
   The board, in an Oct. 18 ruling released Wednesday, reversed a
decision by an administrative law judge and revoked the licenses for
WMJM-AM and WFAV-FM in Cordele, Ga.
   Silver Star can appeal the ruling to the commission within 30
days. John Robert E. Lee, the principal of Silver Star, could not be
reached for comment Wednesday evening.
   The FCC rarely revokes radio and TV station licenses. It has done
so a total of 40 times since 1939, commission spokeswoman Maureen
Peratino said.
   Silver Star bought the stations and two others _ WTJH-AM, East
Point, Ga., and WJIZ-FM, Albany, Ga. _ from James S. Rivers and
members of the Rivers family in 1984. The stations had been
designated for a license renewal hearing because of allegations that
Rivers had misrepresented issues before the FCC.
   In light of the pending hearing, Rivers' sought a discounted
distress sale of the stations and settled upon Lee as a minority
buyer.
   The FCC said the record in the case showed that Lee was primarily
interested in buying WJIZ and that he intended to sell the three
other stations as soon as possible after acquisition.
   The commission also said the record showed that Rivers suggested
that Lee sell the Cordele stations to River's son, Ronald Rivers, a
minority shareholder in the Cordele stations, and Sara Howell, a
Rivers employee.
   The review board said Silver Star abused the distress sale policy
by acquiring at least two stations it did not wish to own or operate
and defying an FCC policy requiring it to maintain those stations
for at least a year before transferring control.
   Additionally, the board noted that Silver Star transferred
control ``to an individual Silver Star knew to have questionable FCC
credentials,'' since Rivers had an interest in the Cordele stations
when they were under investigation by the FCC.
   The FCC review board found that Silver Star ``willfully subverted
the underlying intended purpose of that process. It said the
company's ``willful violation (of the policy) is compounded by
conduct fully as egregious as misrepresentation or lack of candor,
and equally as telling as to its trustworthiness.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
