<1ST_LINE>r f BC-AlleghenyInternational     11-02 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Allegheny International,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allegheny International Approves Reorganization Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International, Inc.'s said Wednesday
its board of directors had approved a plan to emerge from bankruptcy
court protection by selling a substantial interest in the company to
a New York brokerage firm.
   Chairman Oliver S. Travers said Allegheny International would be
merged with a new company to be formed by Donaldson, Lufkin &
Jenrette Securities Corp., with the brokerage contributing $75
million to refinance Allegheny's operations and getting an
unspecified stake in the company in return.
   ``This proposal...brings improved values to the company's
shareholders and creditors,'' Travers said. ``It should hasten our
emerging from Chapter 11...''
   Under the plan _ which must be approved by the U.S. Bankruptcy
Court and other parties in the reorganization _ Allegheny's current
shareholders would get 25 percent of the new company's stock and the
right to buy another 15 percent at the same price paid by Donaldson,
Lufkin & Jenrette.
   The firm also would have the right to add 20-25 percent to the
unspecified interest it would get for its $75 million. The firm
described its initial holding only as substantial.
   Allegheny said it anticipated the plan would provide $698.2
million, consisting of about $537.6 million in cash and $160.6
million in securities, to be distributed to its creditors.
   The company, best known for its Oster and Sunbeam appliances,
filed for reorganization under Chapter 11 of the bankruptcy code on
Feb. 20, 1988, claiming debts of $845 million.
   The proposal provides for negotiations to settle various claims
against the company.
   The plan would be financed through a combination of cash at
Allegheny, bank financing, securities and the brokerage firm's $75
million investment.
   Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette is an independently operated, wholly
owned subsidiary of The Equitable Life Assurance Society of the
United States.
</TEXT>
