<FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 2325EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Boeing-LOT     11-02 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Boeing-LOT,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boeing, Polish Airline Schedule Announcement; May Be Aircraft Order</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENTON, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. and LOT Polish Airlines have
scheduled what they term a major announcement Friday in New York,
amid indications LOT may be ordering Boeing airliners, opening a new
Eastern European market.
   Boeing officials declined to comment Wednesday on any prospective
LOT aircraft order, and representatives for LOT could not be reached
by telephone.
   But spokesmen for Boeing's commercial aircraft division said
earlier this year that they hoped to sell widebody 767 aircraft to
LOT and to other communist-bloc nations.
   While neither confirming nor denying a deal was in the works,
Boeing spokesman John Wheeler said Wednesday that a LOT order would
be the first purchase by a Warsaw Pact nation of new-technology
commercial aircraft.
   Sources indicated any order might be for two or three of the
aircraft, which sell for $50 million to $70 million each, depending
on model.
   This summer, Boeing and three other major Western airplane
manufacturers _ McDonnell Douglas, British Aerospace and Airbus
Industrie _ were granted permission by the Coordinating Committee
for Multilateral Export Control to sell new-generation commercial
jets to Eastern Bloc countries. The Paris-based organization
regulates strategic exports to communist-bloc countries by Western
industrialized nations.
   At the time, Boeing spokesman Bill Clark said Boeing hoped to
sell three widebody 767s to LOT and two 767s to Tarom airline of
Romania. He said there also had been discussions with Malev of
Hungary and Interflug of East Germany.
   Wheeler said Boeing still was discussing a possible 767 sale to
Tarom. And he said Malev has leased Boeing 737s, a smaller twinjet,
through a third party.
   Any sales to Eastern Bloc nations must be approved by the U.S.
departments of State, Commerce and Defense, to ensure that
technology with critical military applications is not transferred to
communist countries.
   Yugoslavia's JAT airline long has been a customer of Boeing's, as
has the Chinese government. Tarom also bought two 707s from Boeing
in 1973.
   Richard Albrecht, Boeing Commercial Airplanes executive vice
president for sales and marketing, in an interview Wednesday would
not discuss any specific negotiations with possible customers, other
to say, ``We're hopeful of receiving some orders from Eastern
European companies.''
   Boeing also would like to sell jets to the Soviet Union, Albrecht
said.
   He said Boeing had talked to the Soviets in the mid-1970s about
selling some airplanes, but nothing ever came of it. However, he
said Boeing officials again talked with Soviet aircraft industry
representatives last year at a San Diego air show.
   ``The largest airline in the world is Aeroflot (the Soviet
national carrier) and I would think that we have some products that
could provide some value to them,'' Albrecht said. ``Whether or not
they would buy them or we could come up with acceptable terms to
satisfy our government with respect to technology transfer is a
question that is up, to a certain degree, to the Soviet Union and
the U.S. government.
   Albrecht said he ``can't imagine the Soviet Union would under any
circumstances permit Aeroflot to rely primarily on aircraft from
outside the Soviet bloc, at least not in today's world.''
   But because Aeroflot is so huge, with thousands of aircraft
ranging from helicopters to transcontinental jets, even if Boeing
supplied only a fraction of its needs, ``it would be very
significant,'' Albrecht said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
